<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Hariri Makes Comeback Amid Deteriorated Economy by Huang Ling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's second and last round
of parliamentary elections Sunday consolidated ex-premier Rafik
Hariri triumphing victory and augmented his chances to be re-named
as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Official results showed that the camp of Hariri, who served as
prime minister from 1992 to 1998, seized 18 of the 19 seats in
pivotal Beirut constituency in the third parliamentary elections
since the devastating 1975-1990 civil war.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese sitting Prime Minister Salim Hoss conceded defeat
Sunday morning. It is the first time in post-independence Lebanon
since 1943 that a reigning prime minister was ousted from the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Hariri's camp has made striking gains in the first round on
August 27, with 41 of the 63 newly elected lawmakers being outright
supporters or sympathizers of Hariri. His allies, Druze chief Walid
Jumblat, Maronite Christian politicians Nassib Lahoud and Sleiman
Frangieh were among the opposition winners. 
</P>
<P>
Hariri therefore can secure 92 seats in the 128-member assembly,
well above the required 86 for premiership.
</P>
<P>
Under constitution, President Emile Lahoud, who sacked Hariri in
1998 and had appeared determined to block the construction tycoon's
comeback, must consult parliament on the choice of a prime minister
and he promised Sunday to observe the constitutional procedure.
</P>
<P>
Analyst said the swift comeback of Hariri, who resigned after
few weeks of bickering with the Maronite president and amid
accusations of plunging the country into huge foreign debts,
reflect Lebanese discontent with the stagnant economy, soaring
unemployment and the government's incompetence in coping with the
snafus.
</P>
<P>
Hoss took over in 1998 on a platform of administrative and
economic reforms to control the 21 billion public debts left behind
by Hariri's massive postwar reconstruction program and reactivate
the economy by boosting tourism and attracting foreign investments,
but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon economy registered a mere 0.5 percent growth last year
and a further slide since the outset of this year. Unemployment
rate remains at more than 30 percent and every year tens of
thousand of youths seek jobs abroad. The huge budget deficit, which
contributed to Hariri's stepdown, has widened further in his
absence.
</P>
<P>
Disappointed Lebanese turned once more to Hariri, hoping he can
remedy the crisis. The construction magnate has promised to
stimulate growth and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
As Safir newspaper said the voters' sympathy for the ex-premier
when President Lahoud set out on lambasting Hariri's six-year reign
and prosecuting his senior aides still lingered.
</P>
<P>
The people "translated that sympathy into an overwhelming
declaration of allegiance to Hariri as the leader of Beirut in the
polls," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Political money also played a big role in the election. It was
reported that Hariri, a billionaire who accumulated his fortunes of
about 4 billion dollars through construction projects in Saudi
Arabia, has earmarked about 50 million dollars for the election.
</P>
<P>
A voter, who declined to be identified, said Sunday morning
outside a polling station near State Stadium that a vote for each
candidate in Hariri's list can be paid 200 dollars, the highest
among the contesting blocs.
</P>
<P>
The tacit consent of Syria, the power broker in Lebanon and
stationing 35,000 troops across the country, also clear the way for
Hariri's comeback. Hariri's return poses no threat to Syria's grip
on Lebanese politics as he and Lahoud, like all major Lebanese
politicians, are solidly in Damascus's camp, local analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Hariri himself has long cultivated ties with Damascus. It is
reported that Hariri has helped set up a holding company in Saudi
Arabia that is keen to invest in Syria.
</P>
<P>
The power in postwar Lebanon is equally divided on sectarian
line, with the president coming from Maronite Christians, the
speaker from Shi'ite Muslims and the prime minister from Sunni
Muslims. So is the case in Lebanese parliament and the 128 seats
are divided in equal parts between Muslims and Christians and the
shares are further sub-divided among the 18 recognized religious
sects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
