<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2002 GMT, September 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Prime Minister Ehud Barak had rejected Israeli army
budget demands for a real-term hike of 250 million U.S. dollars in
the 2001 fiscal year, the Ha'aretz daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, now in New York for the United Nations
Millennium Summit and a critical meeting with United States
President Bill Clinton, had made the decision before he departure
Sunday night, the report said. (Israel-Defense Budget)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Justice Minister Yossi Beilin Tuesday again
lashed out at the idea of forming a joint government with the
right-wing Likud party, and called for continued efforts to push
the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks ahead.
</P>
<P>
Beilin, one of the architects of the Oslo peace accords which
ushered in a new era in Israeli-Palestinian relations, argued that
the government can not give up peace efforts in return for what he
termed as "the deception of an artificial unity government."
</P>
<P>
The minister who has devoted great efforts to nurture the
fragile peace process, charged that such a government would, more
than anything else, signal Israel's willingness to stop making
peace. (Israel-Coalition)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemeni security forces have defused a mine laid in a
sewer in front of Sanaa Tax Office, according to a security source
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The security forces were combing the area for a possible second
mine, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Local police were tipped on Monday night by an unidentified
source that two people had laid the two mines in the sewer, he
noted.By defusing the mine, the area was saved from a blast which
could have caused casualties and property losses, he added.
(Yemen-Mine Scare)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese former premier Rafik Hariri, the biggest
winner in the parliamentary elections, has vowed to boost economy
and activate agriculture and industry if appointed next prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
Hariri, who served as prime minister from 1992 to 1998, made a
striking comeback in the just-concluded parliamentary elections,
with his bloc and allies winning at least a third of the total 128
assembly seats. (Lebanon-Hariri)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- Delay in Palestinian statehood declaration is "on the
cards" if it can serve the purpose of restoring the occupied
Palestinian territories, Palestinian National Council (PNC)
Chairman Salem Zanoun said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Farouk al Kadoumy, director of the political department of the
Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO), said at a press conference
in Cairo on Monday that he did not think a Palestinian state would
be declared on September 13 as long as negotiations were still on.
(Palestine-Statehood-Delay) 
</P>
</TEXT>
