<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Faces Power Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The state-owned Tanzania
Electric Supply Company (TANESCO) needs 20 billion Tanzanian
shillings (about 25 million U.S. dollars) to purchase gas for its
thermal power plant to run at full capacity in the next four
months to avert power rationing due to shortage of rains, a senior
government official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The fund was imperative for the company to meet the power
demand during this period and preserve the decreasing water in the
dams of the hydropower plants, added the official, who declined to
be named.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, TANESCO can not afford to make such an
investment because it has been experiencing financial problems.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the government has taken measures to
cut the 33 billion shillings (about 41.3 million U.S. dollars)
power bills defaulted by government institutions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the one-year tax exemption granted to TANESCO by the
Ministry of Finance from June this year will save the company
billions of shillings.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, about 26 percent of electricity
generated by the company was from thermal plants and the rest from
hydropower plants.
</P>
<P>
At present, some 95 percent of the electricity consumed in
Tanzania is produced by TANESCO, which is also responsible for the
transmission, distribution and sale of electricity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
