<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Sends Parachuters to West Africa While Hostage Negotiations Going on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Britain has sent Parachuters to
West Africa as a "precautionary measure", while negotiations
continue to free six British soldiers being held hostages.
</P>
<P>
The British Broadcast Corporation (BBC) reported on Tuesday
that more than 100 parachuters have been sent to Dakar in Senegal,
near Sierra Leone, where the British soldiers were captured by a
faction of the rebels 11 days ago.
</P>
<P>
The BBC quoted a Ministry of Defense source in London as
stressing that the move was a contingency and said negotiations
with leaders of the notorious West Side Boys remained the priority.
</P>
<P>
Three rounds of talks have been held with the rebels, called
the West Side Boys, over the past three days and on Monday the
British military mission in Sierra Leone said negotiations were
progressing well.
</P>
<P>
The West Side Boys, estimated to have a few hundred members,
are an offshoot of forces loyal to the junta that ruled from May
1997 to February 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, many members are common criminals freed from prison
when the militia took part in the rebel invasion of Freetown in
January 1999, according to the BBC.
</P>
<P>
The group split from the rebel Revolutionary United Front a
year ago and declared allegiance to the government. But after
repeated clashes with government troops, it is now considered a
renegade militia.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the rebels placed demands including the release of
supporters and family, recognition by the Sierra Leone government
and the establishment of an interim government. The Sierra Leone
Government has rejected their demands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Launches Submarine Emergency Drill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 5 (Xinhua) -- In the wake of last month's
deadly Russian submarine incident in the Barents sea, NATO forces
from Italy, the U.S. and Turkey will launch joint exercises off
the Turkish coast to test their abilities to react to a submarine
emergency, NATO sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, several other nations will send observers to the
Gulf of Mersin to watch the exercises, dubbed "Royal Sorbet 2000",
Italian news agency Ansa quoted NATO sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The drill scenario calls for NATO units to provide emergency
help to a submarine trapped at the bottom of the sea, rescuing the
crew and assisting them once they reach the surface.
</P>
<P>
Italy will participate with a surface emergency unit, the Anteo,
and with a Sauro-class submergible craft, Prini.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. will also have a submarine and an emergency assistance
ship, while Turkey will provide the lion's share of equipment:
three submarines, a frigate, three emergency-response units, as
well as Coast Guard boats, helicopters and planes.
</P>
<P>
Observers from Sweden, Argentina, Chile, Australia, Singapore,
Israel, India and Egypt are expected to be present.
</P>
<P>
The August 18 incident involving the Russian submarine Kursk
left 118 sailors dead and triggered an international firestorm of
controversy over delays in rescue attempts and the Russian
government's often conflicting accounts of what caused the nuclear
submarine to explode. 
</P>
</TEXT>
