<HEADLINE> 21 Egyptian Muslims Given Jail Terms for Role in Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-one Egyptian Muslims were
sentenced Tuesday to prison terms of up to 10 years for involvement
in the country's worst violence between Muslims and Christians in
decades.
</P>
<P>
The defendants were found guilty of rioting, looting and setting
fire to shops in the southern town of Dar el-Salam on January 2
after violence spread there from neighboring Kosheh, where 20
Coptic Christians and a Muslim were killed, Egypt's Middle East
News Agency reported. The other 18 accused men in the case were
cleared.
</P>
<P>
Four were given in absentia 10 years imprisonment with hard
labor, four two years, 12 one year and the 21th six months. In
Egypt, the defendants tried in absentia usually receive harsher
sentences than those appear in court.
</P>
<P>
The accused murderers and rioters in the Kosheh case are due to
stand trial in October at the same criminal court in Sohag, 500
kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Clashes broke out in Kosheh on December 31, last year, sparked
by a financial quarrel between a Muslim and a Coptic merchant over
a piece of cloth.
</P>
<P>
Kosheh is one of many towns and villages in southern Egypt that
have large proportions of Copts, who account for around 6 percent
of Egypt's population of 65 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
