<HEADLINE> Delay in Statehood Declaration Possible: PNC Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, September 5 ( Xinhua ) -- Delay in Palestinian statehood
declaration is "on the cards" if it can serve the purpose of
restoring the occupied Palestinian territories, Palestinian
National Council (PNC) Chairman Salem Zanoun said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The postponement is possible should it aim to restore some
parts of our occupied lands or lead to a fresh meeting as promised
by United States President Bill Clinton," said Zanoun in a press
release.
</P>
<P>
Farouk al Kadoumy, director of the political department of the
Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO), said at a press conference
in Cairo on Monday that he did not think a Palestinian state would
be declared on September 13 as long as negotiations were still on.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian government can delay the declaration of its
statehood once more as long as there are convincing reasons," added
Zanoun. He also expressed hope that this postponement would not
harm the Palestinian cause.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian official also said the meeting of the Palestine
Central Council of the PLO on September 9-10 would be very
important and serious as threats posed to the Palestinian
delegation during the failed Camp David summit would be probed.
</P>
<P>
The two-week summit in July between Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Clinton failed to
produce an agreement over key final status issues.
</P>
<P>
Invitations were extended to all Palestinian factions, including
the radical opposition Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) and
Islamic Jihad, which are opposed to the Palestinian authority's
peace talks with Israel, to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
At its meeting held in Gaza on July 1, the central council
decided to declare an independent Palestinian statehood on
September 13, when the interim phase expires.
</P>
<P>
However, after the failure of the Camp David summit, Israel and
the U.S. have repeatedly cautioned the Palestinians against a
unilateral declaration of statehood. 
</P>
