<HEADLINE> Tourists to Cyprus in 2000 Expected to Reach 2.7 Million: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' Commerce, Industry and
Tourism Minister Nicos Rolandis on Tuesday expected the tourist
arrivals to the island this year to reach 2.7 million and relevant
income to be 1.17 billion Cyprus pounds (1.87 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Addressing the two-day "Cyprus Airways Sales Conference", which
started Tuesday in Nicosia, Rolandis said the tourist arrivals to
the island reached 2.43 million last year, a rise of 9.5 percent
compared to 1998, and this year the increase is expected to be
around 10-11 percent, which will mean 2.7 million tourists.
</P>
<P>
Revenues from tourism in 1999 were 1.02 billion pounds (1.63
billion dollars), he added.
</P>
<P>
The conference is attended by 16 directors and representatives
of Cyprus Airways branches in 16 countries, officers of the company
and all those involved in the income department of the air-carrier,
as well as delegates from the Cyprus Tourism Organization (CTO).
</P>
<P>
According to Rolandis, tourism is the powerhouse of Cyprus'
economy in real terms and this year the contribution of tourism to
the GDP (gross domestic product) may reach 21 or 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
The main points raised in Tuesday's session were the priority of
the CTO in the tourism development, the shortage of beds in hotels
this year, the allocation of CTO marketing and promotional funds,
and how to distribute the funds among tour operators, trade
professionals and the public.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Cyprus Airways President Haris Loizides
stressed "
the promotion of winter tourism," and asked for more authority and
flexibility for the CTO officers abroad.
</P>
<P>
He also termed France, Italy and some countries in Eastern
Europe as potential markets for the tourism to Cyprus.  
</P>
</TEXT>
