<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Repeats Sovereignty Claim Over Disputed Gulf Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Foreign Ministry
spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi on Tuesday repeated Iran's claim to
the "complete sovereignty" over three strategic islands in the
Persian Gulf which are also claimed by the United Arab Emirates
(UAE).
</P>
<P>
Iran regards the islands, namely Abu Mussa, Greater and Lesser
Tunbs, as "an inseparable part" of its territory, as it has
repeated on numerous occasions in the past, Asefi was quoted by the
official Islamic Republic News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He added that Iran is ready to discuss the "misunderstanding"
between the two countries by inviting officials from the UAE to
Tehran. But he did not say when the invitations would be extended.
</P>
<P>
At the request of the UAE, the islands issue was raised at the
two-day meeting of Arab League foreign ministers that ended in
Cairo on Monday. Earlier on Saturday, the Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) also called on Iran to cooperate and open direct negotiations
on the islands dispute.
</P>
<P>
Asefi expressed dismay over the Arab League and the GCC's stance
over the dispute, which Iran considers clearly biased to the UAE.
</P>
<P>
Iran took over control of the three Gulf islands, which are
close to the strategic Hormuz Strait, in 1971 after the British
colonist forces retreated from the region. However, both Tehran and
Abu Dhabi claimed sovereignty over the islands.
</P>
<P>
Iran says it is willing for talks to resolve what it calls a
case of "misunderstanding." But the UAE wants a clear agenda and a
specific timetable for talks, and suggests referring the dispute to
international arbitration if negotiations fail.
</P>
<P>
After years of mutual suspicion caused by the 1979 Islamic
revolution in Iran, Iran has been trying to improve relations with
neighboring Arab countries in the GCC, namely the UAE, Saudi
Arabia, Oman, Qatar, Bahrain and Kuwait. But the islands issue
remains a stumbling block for a smooth development of relations.
</P>
<P>
In July 1999, a GCC committee comprising foreign ministers of
Saudi Arabia, Qatar and Oman was set up to mediate and help open
negotiations between the UAE and Iran. Iran pays no heed to the GCC
committee and insists on solving the dispute with the UAE through
bilateral means.
</P>
<P>
So far the committee has achieved little, which is a
disappointment to the UAE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
