<HEADLINE> IMF Not to Resume Aid to Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Finance and Economic
Development Minister Simba Makoni said Tuesday there is no
likelihood the International Monetary Fund (IMF) will resume
balance of payment loan to Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"There are no indications at the moment and I was not expecting
any either," Makoni told the Zimbabwe News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said that with the current government expenditure pattern,
the controversial land acquisition policy and the army still in
the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), the IMF will just
remain aloof to Zimbabwe's need for aid.
</P>
<P>
He said an IMF technical team led by IMF Assistant Director for
Africa Paulo Neuhaus has been in Zimbabwe in the past two weeks to
assess the state of the economy and give advisory policies to the
government.
</P>
<P>
Makoni said the issues discussed included the land acquisition
program, the government's involvement in the DRC war where it has
spent 200 million U.S. dollars since August 1998 and the budget
deficit.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe economy has been in turmoil with inflation and
interest rates reaching record highs while there seems to be no
end to the foreign exchange crisis.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe broke its ties with the IMF last year after the
government missed a number of crucial targets under a 193 million
U.S. dollars stand-by credit arrangement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
