<HEADLINE> Tanzania Encourages Maize Import to Ease Food Shortage  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A statement issued by the Tanzania Information Services says
that importers are encouraged to move food-stocks close to deficit
areas such as Dodoma, Singida, Arusha, Kilimanjaro, Tanga, Mara,
Mwanza, Shinyanga, Tabora and Morogoro regions.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that importers will positively respond to this
notice as support to government efforts to ensuring food security
for all, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Food shortage has been singled out as the major problem the
country will face during the 2000/2001 financial year and the
government has charted out a number of strategies to check the
situation.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye said during the June
Bunge (Parliament) session that there will be a shortage of about
680,840 tons of food crops due to persistent drought.
</P>
<P>
He has been exhorting businessmen to continue importing food as
well as buy food from those areas in the country where there is
surplus.
</P>
<P>
The premier also has been urging livestock keepers to sell
their livestock in exchange for enough food stock to last them
until next season.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the Strategic Grain Reserve silo in Dar
es Salaam needs some 5.9 billion Tanzanian shillings (some 7.4
million US dollars) to replenish food stock.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that since it waived import duty on grain
in June, the famine-hit Kenya has been attracting thousands of
tons of grains from Tanzania though the latter bans grain exports.
</P>
<P>
Due to prolonged drought, millions of Kenyans are also under
the threat of famine. 
</P>
