<HEADLINE> Egyptian Woman, Followers Convicted for Exploiting Islam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian woman and her 14
followers were convicted Tuesday for exploiting Islam.
</P>
<P>
Forty-one-year-old Sheikha Manal Wahid Manei, arrested last
November, was convicted of "provoking civil unrest" by holding
seances in her Cairo flat, during which she claimed the Muslim
Prophet Mohammed appeared, and she was sentenced to five years in
jail with hard labor.
</P>
<P>
Sheikha Manal confessed that she had told some of her followers
not to pray five times a day or make the pilgrimage to Mecca, both
of which are pillars of Islam.
</P>
<P>
The verdict of the state security misdemeanors court said that
the group were found guilty of "exploiting Islam to spread
extremist ideas with the aim of provoking civil unrest and
disdaining the religion," the Middle East News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The court also extended punishments to her 14 followers from
three years imprisonment to a fine of 1,000 Egyptian pounds (around
285 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Sheikha Manal and around 50 supposed followers were arrested on
November 12 in Cairo's poor neighborhood of Sayyeda Zeinab after
one of her seances, but only the seance leader and 15 followers
were brought to trial.
</P>
<P>
One of the defendants died before the trial ended. 
</P>
