<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Government Calls For Substantive Talks on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government on
Tuesday once again called for substantive talks on the Cyprus issue
within the principles set out by the United Nations resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily briefing here, government spokesman
Michalis Papapetrou said the "investigative phase" has been
completed and the U.N.-sponsored Cyprus talks should now go into "
the substance."
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou said Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides is in New York
and will have a meeting with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
He said Clerides will raise ways of making the talks more
substantive as "a dialogue of the deaf cannot continue."
</P>
<P>
The eastern Mediterranean island has remained divided into the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities since 1974 when Turkey
invaded and occupied the northern third after an abortive coup
seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Three rounds of U.N.-sponsored proximity talks have been held
between the two communities, in an effort to pave the way for
substantive negotiations leading to a comprehensive settlement of
the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
A fourth round of talks is scheduled to start on September 12 in
New York.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou noted that until now Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash has been using the procedure in the hope that his
breakaway state in northern Cyprus will be recognized.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Denktash will never achieve the recognition of
his "illegal regime" and "the sooner Denktash comes to acknowledge
this fact the better it is for the Turkish Cypriots."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the possibility of confidence building measures
between the two communities, Papapetrou made it clear that any
ideas relating to this should be put forward in Nicosia, adding
that President Clerides is in New York to discuss the substance of
the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
"The government is willing to discuss confidence building
measures that in no way lead to the recognition of the illegal
regime in the Turkish occupied areas," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared a state in 1983, which is only
recognized by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
