<HEADLINE> Jordan's Opposition Demands Release of Palestinian Hamas Fighter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The influential opposition Muslim
Brotherhood in Jordan has called for the release of a leading Hamas
member after a Palestinian court handed down a 12-year prison term
against him, sources with the Brotherhood said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We demand the release of the hero resistance fighter (against
Israel) Mahmoud Abu Hannud and all other heros held in Palestinian
jails." the Brotherhood said in a statement faxed to reporters
based in Amman.
</P>
<P>
Abu Hannud is a leader of Hamas (the Islamic Resistance
Movement), a radical Palestinian group which remains opposed to the
ongoing peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians and stands
for a holy war to liberate all Palestinian territories from Israeli
occupation.
</P>
<P>
A Palestinian court handed down a 12-year imprisonment again Abu
Hannud after a closed-door session last Friday, accusing him of
belonging to an armed group, illegal weapons possession and aimed
to topple the mainstream Palestinian National Authority headed by
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
He was arrested last week in a hospital in the Palestinian-
controlled town of Nablus where he was getting treatment for his
injuries sustained during an earlier shoot-out with Israeli forces.
</P>
<P>
Three Israeli soldiers were killed mistakenly by their
colleagues during the cross fire on August 26 in a West Bank
village, but Abu Hannud escaped from the Israeli effort to arrest
him.
</P>
<P>
The arrest and verdict against Abu Hannud also triggered
protests in Palestinian self-rule areas, where his supporters took
to the streets to demand his release and called him a hero against
Israeli occupation of Palestinian and other Arab territories.
</P>
</TEXT>
