Jordan will soon witness rapid progress in all fields," Ramadan was
quoted by the INA as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan hailed the stance of Jordan which has been calling for
lifting the decade-old United Nations sanctions off Iraq, and
condemned the United States and Britain for their continuous
bombings of the two so-called no-fly zones in southern and northern
Iraq, set up by Western allies after the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
For their part, the two Jordanian ministers expressed the hope
that their visit will help strengthen the bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, they held separate talks with Iraqi Minister
of Industry and Minerals Adnan Abd Al-Majid Jasim Al-Ani and
Minister of Finance Hikmet Mizban Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
After they arrived here on Monday evening, the two Jordanian
ministers said their visit was aimed at boosting overall
cooperation between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Ramadan visited Amman in July and bilateral relations have since
witnessed a major improvement.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein held talks with the Iraqi
vice president. It was the first time for the Jordanian king to
meet a senior Iraqi official since he assumed the throne in
February last year.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Prime Minister Ali Abu Ragheb, who took office on June
19, has pledged closer ties with Iraq and to help end the U.N.
sanctions imposed on Baghdad after its invasion of Kuwait in August
1990. 
