<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Landmine Clearing Firm Shooting Video on Landmines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean landmine clearing
firm Tuesday said it has begun shooting a film on landmines which
will be part of material used to train non-governmental
organizations and U.N. staff members who work in danger areas.
</P>
<P>
Mine Tech Marketing Manager Elsa Fuchs told the Zimbabwe News
Agency that the video to be provided by her company is an addition
to a handbook with information on landmines in countries ravaged
by war or where war is still going on.
</P>
<P>
"The video will be used together with the handbook," Fuchs said,
adding that the handbook has information on landmines in countries
or regions including Kosovo, Croatia, Somalia, Mozambique and
Angola.
</P>
<P>
A few shots have already been done in Kosovo, she said. "
Instead of going to Kosovo this time we decided to shoot the video
in Zimbabwe."
</P>
<P>
In Zimbabwe there have been 12,500 recorded accidents involving
landmines since 1980, with about 46 people having been killed and
210 injured. Thousands of wild animals and livestock were also
killed or injured.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department estimated that between 60 and 70
million landmines now remain in countries around the world. Among
the worst-affected nations are Afghanistan, Bosnia, Cambodia,
Croatia, Eritrea, Iraq, Somalia, Sudan, Nicaragua and Mozambique.
</P>
</TEXT>
