<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Cluster Bombs Continue to Threaten Civilian Lives in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Cluster bomb submunitions,
landmines and other ordnance have killed or injured nearly 500
people in Kosovo since the end of NATO's military attacks against
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Among the 492 casualties reported to the United Nations Mine
Action Coordinating Center (UNMACC) database in Pristina, cluster
bomb submunitions and anti-personnel mines were the leading cause
of deaths and injuries, with about 36 percent of casualties
resulting from each, according to a report released here Tuesday
by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
</P>
<P>
A cluster bomb is a metal canister that is dropped from an
aircraft. At a pre-set altitude or after a specific time delay,
the canister opens and ejects many dozens or hundreds of
submunitions into the air. These submunitions then fall to the
ground, sometimes with the help of a parachute, where they are
meant to explode upon impact.
</P>
<P>
A significant proportion of the submunitions failed to explode
on impact in Kosovo. Citing conservative NATO estimates, the ICRC
said that it could be presumed that around 30,000 unexploded
cluster bomb submunitions remained after the conflict.
</P>
<P>
As of May 31, 2000, organizations operating under the auspices
of the UNMACC had reported the clearance of 4,069 cluster bomb
submunitions, the ICRC said. These figures do not include the
submunitions or other unexploded ordnance cleared by NATO.
</P>
<P>
Unlike anti-personnel mines, incidents involving the cluster
bomb submunitions usually result in death or injury to several
people as a result of their greater explosive power, the ICRC
stressed. Children appear to be disproportionately at risk of
death or injury from these devices. As compared to those killed or
injured by anti-personnel mines, those injured or killed by
cluster bomb submunitions were 4.9 times as likely to be children
under the age of 14.
</P>
<P>
Based on the finding in Kosovo, the ICRC urged the
international community to consider the following recommendations:
</P>
<P>
-- The use of the cluster bombs and other types of submunitions
against military objectives in populated areas should be
prohibited;
</P>
<P>
-- Users should take responsibility for the clearance of all
unexploded ordnance;
</P>
<P>
-- All necessary technical information concerning the location,
dangers, detection and destruction of cluster bombs and other
munitions should be made available to the U.N. and demining bodies
immediately after the end of hostilities;
</P>
<P>
-- Warning of the threat posed by explosive "remnants of war"
should be provided to civilian populations immediately after their
use in a given area;
</P>
<P>
-- In order to reduce the risk to civilians in future conflicts,
cluster bomb and other submunitions should be fitted with
mechanisms which will ensure their self-destruction immediately
after the device fails to explode upon impact as designed;
</P>
<P>
-- The use of cluster bombs should be suspended until an
international agreement on their use and clearance has been
achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0037 </DOCNO>
