<HEADLINE> Oil Sale Rationed in Part of France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The local governments in
several prefectures of France Tuesday decided to ration the sale
of oil to automobiles because of the blockage of oil storehouses
and refineries by protesting truckers.
</P>
<P>
The prefectural government of Nord in northern France decided
to ration the distribution of oil products in the provinces of
Nord, Pas-de-Calais, Somme and Ardennes in order to avoid oil
shortage for vehicles of prior importance.
</P>
<P>
Many service stations must preserve 25 percent of their stocks
to provide them exclusively for ambulances, taxis, fire engines,
police vehicles and public transport, according to a decree issued
by the prefect.
</P>
<P>
Two prefectural governments in Alsace in eastern France ordered
49 service stations to guarantee oil supply for vehicles of prior
importance and limit sale of oil to individual cars.
</P>
<P>
The prefectural government in Loire, central France, also
ordered 17 service stations to keep oil stocks for emergency
services.
</P>
<P>
Truckers have been blocking oil storehouses, pipeline terminals
and refineries across France for a second consecutive day on
Tuesday to protest the rise of fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
France has called on the European Union to exert pressure on
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to
increase production, after the oil prices rose to a 10-year record
high Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
