<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch UMTS Auction Meets Objective: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Dutch government officials
said on Tuesday that the Dutch auction of the UMTS licenses had
met the objectives of the government policy.
</P>
<P>
UMTS stands for universal mobile telecommunications standard,
the latest generation of cellular phone service. UMTS boasts of a
transmission speed 40 times faster than that of the existing GSM
standard.
</P>
<P>
The higher telecommunication speed makes possible new
capabilities such as mobile phone connection to the Internet and
video displays.
</P>
<P>
State Secretary Monique de Vries and Finance Minister Gerrit
Zalm said in a joint statement received here that it would be
misleading to compare the Dutch auction proceeds with those in
Britain and Germany.
</P>
<P>
The final result of the Dutch UMTS auction meets the widely
shared objectives of the government policy, and the Dutch
telecommunications policy is aimed at generating a first-class
telecom market by the early provision of high-grade infrastructure
and services so that the Netherlands will remain one of the front-
runners in Europe, they said.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands put five third-generation UMTS licenses at
stake in the July auction and the government set forth an opening
price at 470 million Dutch guilders (202 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Dutch auction proceeds finally amounted to 6 billion
guilders (2.6 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The licenses on offer will entitle holders to use allocated
frequencies for the provision of services until December 31, 2016.
The UMTS services turn mobile telephones into multimedia devices.
</P>
<P>
Eight companies took part in the auction. They included KPN
Mobile and Libertel, the largest and second largest mobile phone
operators in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands is the second European country after Britain to
have auctioned UMTS licenses. In April, the British government
got 22.5 billion pounds (34 billion U.S. dollars) from the auction
sales of five UMTS licenses, more than five times the sum
previously expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hariri Vows to Remove Barriers Against Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese former premier Rafik
Hariri, the biggest winner in the parliamentary elections, has
vowed to boost economy and activate agriculture and industry if
appointed next prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Hariri, who served as prime minister from 1992 to 1998, made a
striking comeback in the just-concluded parliamentary elections,
with his bloc and allies winning at least a third of the total 128
assembly seats.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference held in his luxurious residence in Beirut
Tuesday morning, Hariri expressed thanks, on behalf of his "dignity
election group," to all Beirut people. "I will not forget their
confidence to us and the responsibility on our shoulders," he
said. "We should develop our economic relationship with Arabic
country and eliminate those existing barricades of our regulations
and laws in the economic life. We also should create jobs for our
youths," Hariri said.
</P>
<P>
He ruled out the possibility of cutting down on budget next year
if he becomes the premier. "On the contrary, we will increase the
expenditure of government. We will consider hire more employees,"
he said. The huge budget deficit resulted from Hariri's massive
post-war reconstruction program has contributed his resignation in
1998.
</P>
<P>
He promised his group will work for Beirut's interest, find out
what local people need and restore the city's "vanguard" role in
the fields of education, economy and humanitarian.
</P>
<P>
Hariri said he hoped to activate "domestic dialog" and "widen
participation" in national reconstruction in a bid to restore
Lebanon's former status in local and international scene.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he attached importance to the freedom of expression
and promised to respect the constitution, human rights and reserve
public freedom in the country. "We shall give judicatory
departments full independence in our political life," he added.
</P>
<P>
As to the possibility of President Emile Lahoud's opposition to
his designation as premier, Hariri said it is "a rumor form
authority" and he believe it will not take place.
</P>
<P>
Under Lebanese constitution, a prime minister's designation must
get approval of the president and at least 86 deputies in the 128-
member parliament.
</P>
<P>
Hariri is expected to be able to secure 92 seats and Lahoud, who
sacked Hariri two years ago and had appeared determined to bloc the
construction tycoon's comeback, has promised to observe the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
Besides, he reiterated the importance of the relationship
between Lebanon and Syria. "Our relations are very stable and
critical," he said.
</P>
<P>
Syria, the main power broker of Lebanon and stationing 35,000
troops across the country, had publicly said that it would remain
neutral in the elections. Syrian official sources earlier said "it
is Lebanon's affair and it will support president Lahoud's
decision." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
