<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 80,000 Afghan Refugees Repatriated From Iran Since April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Some 83,777 Afghan refugees have
returned home from Iran since April 8 as part of a "voluntary
repatriation program," the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) announced here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The program will continue until October in line with an
agreement signed between the Iranian government and the UNHCR, said
Toshiro Odahsima, who is in charge of the UNHCR office in Tehran,
the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, signed in February, some 100,000 Afghan
refugees are to be repatriated to Afghanistan in six months.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR puts the total number of Afghan refugees in Iran at 1.
4 million, of which some 70,000 are living in Iran illegally.
</P>
<P>
Afghan refugees have been blamed for contributing to the high
rate of unemployment in Iran. Labor Minister Hussein Kamali said in
May that about 2 million refugees, most of them Afghans, are
working illegally in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Last month, some 154 members of Iran's Majlis (parliament) also
urged President Mohammad Khatami's government to repatriate Afghan
refugees living in Iran to their civil war-torn homeland.
</P>
<P>
"The increasing number of Afghan refugees and their long
presence here has given rise to numerous problems for Iranian
citizens," the Majlis members said in an open letter to the
president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
