<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Concerned About High Oil Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The French government on Tuesday
expressed its concern about the high oil prices, which have
triggered off widespread protests in France by truckers, taxi
drivers, farmers and workers in fuel products-consuming
industries.
</P>
<P>
"We consider the present situation of oil prices and their
volatility as worrying and we attach great importance to the
stability (of oil prices) for consumer countries," French Foreign
Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret said.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices rose to their record high in 10 years in London as
the market considered an increase in oil production by Saudi
Arabia alone as insufficient to make up for the deficiency of
stocks in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, a main member of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC), said last week that it would increase
oil production to one million barrels a day from 500,000 barrels
in order to alleviate the pressure on the market.
</P>
<P>
French Transport Minister Jean-Claude Gayssot on Tuesday asked
the European Union (EU) to exert pressure on OPEC to increase its
oil production.
</P>
<P>
French truckers, farmers and taxi drivers have been staging
demonstrations, blocking oil storehouses and refineries for the
last two days in protest against the rising fuel prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: U.N. Millennium Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Millennium Summit
will be held September 6-8 at the U.N. headquarters in New York,
with the theme of "the Functions of the U.N. in the 21st Century."
</P>
<P>
The idea of convening such a summit was first raised by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan in 1997 and was adopted at the 53rd U.
N. Assembly on December 17, 1998.
</P>
<P>
More than 160 heads of state or government will attend the
summit, making it the largest ever convention in the U.N. history.
Its size will exceed the celebrations in 1995 of the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the U.N.
</P>
<P>
The participants will focus on the issues of peace and
development, improvement of the functions of the U.N.
organizations, economic globalization, the intensification of
north-south differences and the marginalization of the African
continent.
</P>
<P>
Besides elaborating their stances on major international issues
at the summit, the leaders will also attend four geographical
round tables to discuss the report on the working plan of the U.N.
in the 21st century, submitted by Annan in April.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the African, Asian, East European, and Latin
American and Caribbean blocs will each hold interactive round-
table meetings. Countries belonging to no particular blocs will
attend these round tables after consulting with chairman of the U.
N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
A political declaration will come out of the summit.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Security Council member states and the five
permanent members of the Security Council will each hold a summit,
while the U.N. Economic and Social Council will hold an informal
high-level meeting on information technology at the time of the
summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, September 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA -- The Belarussian government reiterated on Monday its
rebuff to the enlargement of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), considering it "making the political
situation in Europe more tense."
</P>
<P>
President of Belarus Alexander Lukashenko, who will conclude
his visit to Cuba on Tuesday, said at a press conference in the
capital of Havana that his country keeps a firm opposition to the
enlargement of the military organization.
</P>
<P>
President Lukashenko was the first leader of the former Soviet
republics to make a call against the NATO's eastward expansion. (
Belarus-NATO-Expansion)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Justice Minister Yossi Beilin Tuesday
again lashed out at the idea of forming a joint government with
the right-wing Likud party, and called for continued efforts to
push the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks ahead.
</P>
<P>
Beilin, one of the architects of the Oslo peace accords which
ushered in a new era in Israeli-Palestinian relations, argued that
the government can not give up peace efforts in return for what he
termed as "the deception of an artificial unity government."
</P>
<P>
The minister who has devoted great efforts to nurture the
fragile peace process, charged that such a government would, more
than anything else, signal Israel's willingness to stop making
peace. (Israel-Coalition-Minister)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOGADISHU -- At least 25 people were killed and more than 18
others wounded after heavy fighting erupted Monday morning between
two rival clans in northwestern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
According to eye witnesses, nearly 100 heavily armed militiamen
from the Galje'l clan attacked a village near Jowhar town, 90
kilometers north of Mogadishu. The village was mainly inhabited by
the Hawadleh clansmen.
</P>
<P>
A counterattack from the Hawadleh clan later spread the armed
confrontation between the two clans to another village nearby,
which further increased the casualties. (Somalia-Clan-Fight)
</P>
</TEXT>
