<HEADLINE> Beijing Police Chief Urges Districts to Crack Down on Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Qiang Wei, police chief of
Beijing, signed special contracts today with heads of sub-public
security bureaus in three districts to curb rampant criminal
activities.
</P>
<P>
Under the contracts, police officers in Chaoyang, Haidian and
Fengtai districts will be promoted, rewarded or dismissed in
accordance with the results of their work.
</P>
<P>
In an address at the signing ceremony, Qiang urged the sub-
bureaus, which are made up of 33 police stations, to improve the
local security situation within one year.
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed at better safeguarding social stability of
Beijing by maintaining the "Strike Hard" attitude toward criminals,
in an effort to create a sound social environment for the city to
contend for hosting Olympiad 2000, according to the police chief.
</P>
<P>
The three districts which have drawn special concerns from the
authorities are where lots of China's "floating population" are
believed to be responsible for most of the criminal cases
uncovered in the areas.
</P>
<P>
Last year, these districts accounted for half of the crimes
reported in the city. This year, local police have focused on
cracking down on thieves, robbers and swindlers in these areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
