<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sri Lanka's Fighting Dies Down As Election Campaigns  Kick Off  By Lian Guohui </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The latest fierce fighting
between Sri Lankan government troops and Tamil Tiger rebels died
down on Tuesday as a record number of candidates has officially
kicked off campaigns for the October 10 general elections.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of soldiers and rebels were reported to have been
killed in the heavy fighting in the northern Jaffna peninsula. The
military put its losses at 132 soldiers killed and some 800
wounded while claiming to have killed some 300 rebels of
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) and wounded another 300.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Ariya Rubasinghe said troops are
consolidating the newly captured areas in Colombuturai area, in
the eastern outskirts of Jaffna town.
</P>
<P>
The offensive began on Sunday when thousands of troops - backed
by ground attack aircraft - advanced into Colombuturai, Sarasalai,
Maduvil and Nunavil which were lost to the rebels earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry said the LTTE rebels had launched two
ferocious counter-attacks against military positions at
Colombuturai on Monday, but were repelled.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released from their London office on Tuesday,
the LTTE rebels said they had repulsed a major offensive launched
by the Sri Lankan Army in the Jaffna peninsula killing at least
150 soldiers and injuring over 1,000 after two days of fighting.
</P>
<P>
The statement said 60 rebels were killed in the heavy fighting
on Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
The military said it had recovered the bodies of 69 rebels and
would hand over 37 of them which were in good condition to rebels
through the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
</P>
<P>
The ICRC said they were in contact with both sides over the
issue of returning bodies. The clandestine radio of the LTTE said
on Tuesday that the rebels were planning to hand over 50 bodies of
soldiers to the ICRC.
</P>
<P>
The latest bloodshed erupted as the campaigns officially kicked
off after nominations closed Monday for the October parliamentary
elections.
</P>
<P>
A record number of 5,048 candidates from 29 political parties
and 99 independent groups submitted their nominations to contest
the 225 seats in the parliament. The last general elections in
1994 saw only 1,449 candidates trying to win over voters.
</P>
<P>
Some 12 million voters will go to the polls on October 10 to
elect their representatives according to the proportional
representation system.
</P>
<P>
Nine seats are allocated for the war-torn Jaffna district,
which the LTTE rebels want to claim as part of an independent
Tamil homeland called Eelam. Tamil parties, which could not
contest the large urban area of the Jaffna peninsula in the last
parliamentary elections in 1994 because the region was controlled
by the LTTE, are mounting an election campaign in the area despite
threats from the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE is fighting a 17-year war against majority Sinhalese
dominated government in a bid to carve out a separate state for
minority Tamils in the country's north and east. More than 60,000
people have been killed in the ethnic war.
</P>
<P>
More than a month before the vote, election fever has already
swept Sri Lanka, with posters of candidates everywhere. Although
there are a record number of parties and independent groups
contesting the elections, the battle is expected to be dominated
by the ruling People's Alliance (PA) of President Chandrika
Kumaratunga and the main opposition United National Party (UNP)
led by former premier Ranil Wickremesinghe.
</P>
<P>
The October election is widely seen as a referendum on the
constitutional reform proposals which seek to devolve greater
power to the regions of the country, particularly the Jaffna
peninsula, where the minority Tamil community dominate.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga has made her constitutional reform bid the main
plank for the PA to seek a fresh mandate from the electorate. The
president has said she will press ahead with the controversial
power-sharing plan even if she fails to muster the required two
thirds majority in the parliament. She promises to implement her
new constitution within two months of coming to power.
</P>
<P>
In August this year Kumaratunga had to shelve the draft
constitution in the parliament as the UNP refused to support.
Nationalist Sinhalese groups and senior Buddhist monks have also
rejected the draft constitution on the grounds that it might lead
to the disintegration of the country.
</P>
<P>
In its elections manifesto released last weekend, the UNP said
it would not rush any constitutional reforms, but would open
dialogue with all parties in and outside parliament while raising
the professional standard of the military.
</P>
<P>
The UNP said it hoped to set up a military council comprising
the chiefs of the armed forces to conduct offensive operations and
establish a committee of retired generals who will advise the
armed forces on strategy and tactics.
</P>
<P>
Security in and around Colombo has been stepped up in advance
of the elections as the government is importing a fleet of bullet-
proof cars for ruling party leaders who are likely targets for
LTTE's suicide bombings.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believed the elections on October 10 is vital as
it will determine the fate of President Kumaratunga's draft
constitution and the prospects for peace in the war-torn country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
