<HEADLINE> 25 Killed in Clashes Between Rival Clans in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 5 (Xinhua) -- At least 25 people were
killed and more than 18 others wounded after heavy fighting
erupted Monday morning between two rival clans in northwestern
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
According to eye witnesses, nearly 100 heavily armed militiamen
from the Galje'l clan attacked a village near Jowhar town, 90
kilometers north of Mogadishu. The village was mainly inhabited by
the Hawadleh clansmen.
</P>
<P>
A counterattack from the Hawadleh clan later spread the armed
confrontation between the two clans to another village nearby,
which further increased the casualties.
</P>
<P>
The fighting resulted from a conflict between the two clans in
Jowhar town last month, in which 20 people from both sides were
killed.
</P>
<P>
Somalia's different clans frequently confronted with each other
over territory and the country has been divided into different
clan-based fiefdoms since 1991 when the then president Mohamed
Siad Barre was overthrown.
</P>
<P>
The election of Abdiqassim Salad Hassan as Somali president
during the Djibouti peace conference has raised hope among people
for the forming of a central government in 10 years. But Hassan
still faces stiff opposition from some warlords in Somalia.
</P>
</TEXT>
