<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Accession to EU to Complete by End of 2003: Prodi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Romano Prodi, president of
the commission of the European Union (EU) said on Tuesday that the
first accession for more countries to join the EU will complete by
late 2003.
</P>
<P>
"I am determined to make sure that the first accession will
actually take place by the end of this commission's term in office,
" said Prodi while addressing EU diplomats stationed in other
countries for their biannual meeting.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that EU expansion is one of the two priorities of
the current five-year-term commission. The other priority is
internal reform.
</P>
<P>
"There can be no doubt that this commission will live up to the
historic challenge to unite Europe during the years to come. I
place the utmost importance on the commission's proactively
carrying forward the enlargement process," he said.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's remarks came after a commissioner had caused a panic
about a German referendum on the EU's eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
Guenther Verheugen, European commissioner in charge of
enlargement, has told the German newspaper Sueddeutsch Zeitung
that the German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder should ask the German
public how they feel about the enlargement.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the commission clarified on Monday that what
Verheugen meant was to get the broadest possible public support
for the process of enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Prodi has asked the commissioner for an explanation on his
remarks to the German newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The EU started a publicity campaign about the enlargement in
August.
</P>
<P>
It began talks in 1998 with Hungary, Poland, the Czech Republic,
Estonia, Slovenia and Cyprus about their entry into the union.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, Romania, Latvia, Lithuania, Slovakia and Malta have
been added to the applicant country list that has started
accession negotiations. Turkey is also on the list but will enter
the negotiations a few years later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
