<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Justice Minister Rejects Coalition with Likud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Justice Minister
Yossi Beilin Tuesday again lashed out at the idea of forming a
joint government with the right-wing Likud party, and called for
continued efforts to push the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks
ahead.
</P>
<P>
Beilin, one of the architects of the Oslo peace accords which
ushered in a new era in Israeli-Palestinian relations, argued that
the government can not give up peace efforts in return for what he
termed as "the deception of an artificial unity government."
</P>
<P>
The minister who has devoted great efforts to nurture the
fragile peace process, charged that such a government would, more
than anything else, signal Israel's willingness to stop making
peace.
</P>
<P>
In late August, Prime Minister Ehud Barak reached out to the
opposition Likud in a surprise move, saying that if the peace talks
fall through, the ruling One Israel would set up a national unity
government with Likud, and suggested that Likud leader Ariel Sharon
would be qualified for the post of foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Barak has since been repeating the overture, which is seen by
some observers as a scare tactic to pressure Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat into showing more flexibility in his positions.
</P>
<P>
In response to request not to pressure Arafat, Barak, who is in
New York to attend the U.N. Millennium Summit, extended a few more
weeks for the peace talks to run its course.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan on Monday,
Barak said he would give the peace process another "few weeks"
before turning his attention inward and move to form a national
unity government with Likud.
</P>
<P>
Barak also called Sharon Monday night to brief the opposition
leader on his talks in New York. Sharon reiterated Tuesday that
they did not discuss the possibility of a national unity government
if Israel and the Palestinians fail to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
Sharon told Israel Radio that "I spoke to Barak...He told me he
wanted to hear 'new ideas'...These are very dangerous for Israel's
future."
</P>
<P>
"This government is a failure. We are doing everything possible
to change it," Sharon said.
</P>
<P>
Following the collapse of the July Camp David peace summit, the
U.N. Millennium Summit is widely seen as a great opportunity for
the Israelis and Palestinians to break the current deadlock in the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Barak is to meet U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on
Tuesday ahead of his meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Wednesday. Clinton is also to meet Arafat in a bid to further
advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
A trilateral meeting between Barak, Arafat and Clinton has not
been scheduled, but sources here have not ruled out such a
possibility.
</P>
<P>
Officials in Barak's delegation to the United Nations have
expressed pessimism over the chances of securing a breakthrough in
the summit.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, observers here believe both Barak and Arafat will
value the opportunity at hand until all efforts to reactivate the
peace process are exhausted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Oman has started building the first phase of a new
tourist village worth 150 million U.S. dollars in the southern
coastal town of Mirbat to attract more holiday makers to the Gulf
Arab state, Gulf News daily reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The first phase of the Mirbat tourist village has already
started and the other three phases are expected to start soon,"
said Akbar Raja, project coordinator of the Dhofar Tourism Company.
</P>
<P>
He said the project was being funded by private shareholders and
loans from financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Oman attracts some 650,000 tourists a year, who mostly visit its
long coastline, rugged mountains and desert scenery. Omani hotels
earned about 42 million rials (109 million U.S. dollars) from
foreign tourists in 1999, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Arab state is on a drive to diversify its economy away
from oil and gas revenues which make up about 70 percent of its
income.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The Moroccan Finance Ministry has rejected the idea of
devaluating the national currency, dirham, despite the losses
suffered by the country's economy from the downturn in the exchange
rate between euro and U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
A source with the ministry said such a notion was unacceptable
at present due to its threat to the stability of prices in local
market.
</P>
<P>
The source expressed grave concern over the prospects of
Moroccan exports in view of the pressures brought about on the euro
to which dirham is linked within the international currency
basket.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign trade is likely to be negatively affected and we are
making new counterpart arrangements," he said without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- An Omani joint stock company is expected to soon
become the first firm from a Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) member
to be listed on the Doha Securities Market (DSM).
</P>
<P>
More are expected to be listed once the GCC electronic linkage
is finalized, Gulf News daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The DSM gave its initial approval to the listing of Oman's
Trans Gulf for Industrial Investment," said a DSM spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"Forms and procedures now have to be undertaken by the company
for the listing. Any other GCC company can submit an application
and DSM committee will examine it. DSM laws allow GCC firms
listing," he added.
</P>
<P>
So far, according to the spokesman, no other GCC firm has
applied for DSM listing.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The total combined budget of commercial banks operating
in Yemen stood at 258 billion rials (1.6 billion U.S. dollars) in
the first half of this year, up by 10.5 percent from the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
A report issued by the Central Bank of Yemen said that national
banks secured 61.7 percent of the banking activities in Yemen,
leaving the remnant 38.3 percent to Arab foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Dubai's exhibition season began on Monday with the
opening at the Dubai World Trade Center of "Chemtex 2000", an
international expo for petrochemical and chemicals industries.
</P>
<P>
"It is a bigger expo this time with 80 companies participating
now compared to 60 firms two years ago," said Abdul Rahman Al
Mutaiwee, director general of the Dubai Chamber of Commerce and
Industry, after the inaugural ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Companies from over 15 countries are taking part in the show
which will be open for the next three days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
