<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libyan Envoy Back to Manila to Speed up Hostages' Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Libyan Ambassador Rajab
Azzarouk returned to Manila Tuesday to work for the release of the
remaining hostages, including American Jeffrey Schilling, being
held captive by the Abu Sayyaf group.
</P>
<P>
When arriving, together with another Libyan negotiator
Mohhammad Hassan, arrived at the Manila International Airport in
the afternoon, Azzarouk said he is glad to be back again and
expressed optimism that the hostages would be released in due time.
</P>
<P>
He said he was sent by Libyan leader Moammar Khadaffy to hold
fresh negotiations with the Abu Sayyaf for the speedy release of
the remaining captives.
</P>
<P>
When asked if he is also negotiating for Schilling, he said he
will do it as a sign of goodwill to the American people.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the ongoing negotiation is being coursed
through non-government organizations in Mindanao so that all the
remaining captives would be released unharmed.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the American hostage abducted on August 28, the
rebel group is still holding five of the original group of 21
hostages snatched from Malaysia's Sipadan island on April 23, and
two French journalists seized in Jolo last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
