<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Claims No Swap Deal on Hostages' Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
not about to release suspected terrorist Hadji Ahmad Upao, who is
believed to be Abu Sayyaf leader Abu Sabaya's kin, just to get the
group to negotiate with government negotiators for the release of
its American hostage.
</P>
<P>
In a press briefing Tuesday, Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora
said the case of Upao is an entirely different matter that should
not be dragged into the hostage case.
</P>
<P>
"His uncle, assuming that he is in fact Sabaya's uncle, was
picked up in a completely unrelated matter," Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
Reports earlier quoted Sabaya as allegedly saying the Abu
Sayyaf will not negotiate with the government for the release of
American Jeffrey Schilling unless his relative, referring to 73-
year old Upao, is released.
</P>
<P>
Upao was arrested by the Presidential Anti-Organized Crime Task
Force for allegedly plotting the abduction and murder of Fr. Rhoel
Gallardo.
</P>
<P>
The suspect was also believed to be part of the Abu Sayyaf
faction that kidnapped a priest, teachers and pupils in Basilan in
March. The priest and two other captives were killed by the Abu
Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the government would be willing to give up Upao should
Sabaya convey his request through any of the government
negotiators dealing with the Abu Sayyaf, Zamora said "it is hard
to engage in exchange deals." 
</P>
</TEXT>
