<HEADLINE> Border Posts Along Guinea Bissau-Senegal Frontier Closed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- All border posts along the
frontier between Guinea-Bissau and Senegal have been closed, a
source of the Interior Ministry of Guinea-Bissau was quoted by the
Portuguese news agency Lusa as saying on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the source, the Senegalese authorities closed on
Saturday the only border post between Sao Domingos in northwest
Guinea-Bissau and Mpack in Senegal. This crossing leads to
Ziguinchor, capital of southern Senegal's Casamance Province,
where separatist rebels have waged an 18-year rebellion against
the Dakar government.
</P>
<P>
A week ago the border at Cambadju in northeast Guinea-Bissau
was closed after local authorities on the Senegalese side
protested against delays in returning allegedly stolen cattle.
</P>
<P>
On August 18, President of Guinea-Bissau Kumba Iala paid an
official visit to Senegal, during which he discussed with his
Senegalese counterpart Abdoulaye Wade on the issue of the border
situation.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents promised to study an "ideal schedule" for
Guinea-Bissau to undertake its commitment to mediate between the
Dakar government and the separatist Casamance Democratic Forces
Movement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, chiefs of staff of Guinea-Bissau and Senegal, have
pledged never to use force against each other and to collaborate
in tightening border controls to avoid arms trafficking and cattle
rustling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 72 Percent of Ethiopian Children Out of School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Seventy-two percent of
school age children in Ethiopia do not have access to formal
education, the government-owned Ethiopian Herald newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a report presented to a two-day workshop
on basic education in Ethiopia as saying that the drop-out at the
first cycle of the primary education is as high as 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
The disparity between states and gender gap remains high even
though the government budget expenditure on education has reached
more than 15 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
During the workshop, educationists urged the whole society to
make efforts to popularize basic education in the country to
promote the quality of the population.
</P>
<P>
Although schools intake, enrollment rate, text ration per
student and other indicators of the level of basic education in
Ethiopia has shown remarkable rise over the past five years,
rigorous efforts should be deployed to meet the national education
program, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
