<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Launches U.S. Satellite with Proton Rocket </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Tuesday launched a U.
S. satellite from the Baikonur cosmodrome in Kazakhstan, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Proton-K rocket carrying a Sirius-2 satellite was blast off
from Baikonur at 1:44 p.m. Moscow time (0944 GMT), Interfax said,
quoting the press service of the Russian strategic missile force.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's launch of a Proton rocket was the 10th blastoff this
year and the 275th since the rocket came into use. Four more
launches are scheduled for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Sirius-2 satellite is intended for broadcasting high-
quality radio programs that will be received by mobile radio-sets.
</P>
<P>
It is the second launch of Sirius satellites with a Proton
rocket, the first being on July 1, Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Provides Turkey with Vaccine for Foot-and-Mouth Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union on Tuesday
shipped the first lot of a special vaccine to Turkey to combat the
foot-and-mouth disease.
</P>
<P>
The trivalent vaccine was formulated from antigen stocks kept
at the EU's antigen bank.
</P>
<P>
The vaccine is expected to combat an exotic strain of the foot-
and-mouth disease in ruminants in the Thrace region of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The foot-and-mouth disease is a highly contagious disease of
ruminants and swine, known to cause significant economic losses to
livestock farmers.
</P>
<P>
In general an outbreak of the disease immediately leads to
restrictions on international trade in livestock and in products
such as fresh meat, milk and certain milk products originating
from the country affected.
</P>
<P>
The disease in animals, however, does not pose any danger to
human health.
</P>
<P>
The European Union follows a non-vaccination policy against the
foot-and-mouth disease. Vaccines are only used in emergency
situations. The EU maintains a bank with about 30 million vaccine
equivalent doses of different antigens of the foot-and-mouth
disease virus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SKorean Survey Finds Alarming Hormone Disrupting Substances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A comprehensive official survey
has discovered human hormone disrupting substances at alarming
levels in South Korea, said the Environment Ministry Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A 17-month monitoring program and analysis of the ecosystem of
South Korea, which ended last month, found endocrine disrupters at
113 locations, including rivers, streams, air and soil, said the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
It is the first comprehensive survey by the South Korean
government.
</P>
<P>
Dioxin, known as a carcinogen, measured at high levels at
Panwol industrial complexes in Ansan, South Korea, at 8.62 pgTEQ (
picogram toxic equivalent quantity) per cubic meter, much higher
than the average 2.726pgTEQ.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that the dioxin levels were generally higher
in the air and soil than in waters, as much as 2.5 times more than
the average in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Fish, frogs and other living organisms sampled from the tainted
locations were found to have defective reproductive systems.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said it will introduce a law designed to contain
the spread of toxic substances and start a special monitoring
system in the areas that were found to be contaminated by these
substances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
