<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Laborer in W.W.II Dies (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Liu Huanxin, the eldest son of Liu Lianren, said that his
father's health severely deteriorated due to the hardship he had
experienced as a laborer and his 13 years of cave life.
</P>
<P>
Liu Lianren suffered from a gastric ulcer which led to cancer
in 1998. He died of canner on September 2.
</P>
<P>
Historical data showed that more than 40,000 Chinese youth and
prisoners of war were transported to Japan by Japanese invaders
during World War II. They were forced to do hard labor for 35
Japanese companies in 135 workplaces. Of the prisoners, 6,769
died from either the rough voyage or hardship.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yibo, a professor with the War Research Institute in
northeast China's Liaoning Province, said that the Chinese
laborers have instituted legal proceedings during recent years.
None of them has won any of the 46 cases they have initiated.
</P>
<P>
On May 19, two former Chinese laborers for Mitsubishi and
Mitsui filed a suit in the supreme court in California, the United
States, on behalf of themselves and 8,200 other Chinese laborers.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that the WW II Chinese laborers asked
for compensation outside of China and Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
