<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Budget Deficit to Increase Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's budget deficit in
the next fiscal year is expected to reach 52.9 trillion rupiah (7.
557 billion U.S. dollars) or higher than the current figure which
stands at 44 trillion rupiah (6.285 billion dollars), 3.7 percent
of the country's gross domestic product, an official said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Director General for State Budget at the Ministry of Finance,
Anshari Ritonga said the increase of budget deficit in the fiscal
year 2001 is largely due to the huge financial burden that should
be carried out by the government.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, it is determined that the country's 2001 budget
will still not be able to give significant stimulus to the
economic activities," Ritonga said.
</P>
<P>
He said that under the draft of the next state budget, the
country's expenditures are targeted to reach 283.3 trillion rupiah
(40.471 billion U.S. dollars) while the income was only targeted
at 230.4 trillion rupiah (32.914 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ritonga also said the government will try to get foreign
borrowing to overcome the deficit, saying that Indonesia still
needs huge foreign borrowing.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign borrowing is expected to reach 27 trillion rupiah (3.
857 billion U.S. dollars) for the last two years," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
