<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Sailors Bowled over by Sydney Strong Winds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A freak wind blast of 40 knots
caused massive damage to several Olympic class yachts on Sydney
Harbour Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Olympic sailors were caught unawares when the stiff breeze hit,
with many suffering broken masts.
</P>
<P>
Sydney's water police said the harbour was temporarily awash
with battered yachts but there were no reports of serious injuries
to any sailors.
</P>
<P>
Australian Tornado pair Darren Bundock and John Forbes were one
of the first crews hit by the wind gust and were unceremoniously
flipped over.
</P>
<P>
"We did a bit of cartwheel -- the wind just came in and flipped
us over big time, we didn't have a chance," Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
"You couldn't really see it coming. One minute it was a steady
10 to 15 knots and then it was 40 knots and it stayed like that
for four or five hours."
</P>
<P>
As the pair made their way ashore, Forbes said there were
already signs of disaster.
</P>
<P>
The Woollahra Sailing Club was hosting a regatta when the
strong winds hit.
</P>
<P>
Club spokesman Lou Carter said four 49ers -- from Denmark,
Ukraine, Sweden and Japan -- had to be towed ashore because the
winds were too strong to sail in.
</P>
<P>
Four other 49ers -- all non-Olympic yachts from Australia --
were temporarily abandoned along the eastern shore of the harbour,
where they were tied down until the wind eased.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
