<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Mark 1st "World Space Week" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- China plans to hold a series
of activities to mark the first "World Space Week", according to
Luo Ge, director of the committee to prepare the celebrations.
</P>
<P>
In November 1999, the United Nations accepted a proposal at the
Third UN Outer Space Meeting to celebrate "World Space Week" from
October 4-10 every year.
</P>
<P>
This year, the first year to mark the festival, the United
Nations will hold celebrations in New York and Vienna, while the
governments of at least 26 countries have decided to launch their
own programs to mark the event, according to Luo.
</P>
<P>
China's programs include a space technology exhibition at the
Military Museum of the Chinese People's Revolution in Beijing from
September 28 to October 6, a celebration conference to be held at
Beijing University, and a ceremony at the National Library for the
launching of two books on the development of space technology, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
A copy of China's first experimental manned space shuttle will
be on display at the exhibition for the first time, the official
said. Meanwhile, the exhibition will be the first of its kind to
give a complete introduction on the development of space
technology in the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
The programs are designed to create greater awareness among the
public, especially young people, about space technology, according
to the official.
</P>
<P>
Luo reiterated the Chinese government's stance on the peaceful
utilization and development of space technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
