<HEADLINE> Three Countries to Stay out of COMESA's Free Trade Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic Republic of the
Congo (DRC), Swaziland and Namibia have asked to stay out of the
Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) Free Trade
Area (FTA) to be effective this October, Zambia Daily Mail
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The three countries have asked for permission to suspend
proceedings before joining the FTA to allow them iron out certain
difficulties in their respective countries, according to COMESA
public relations official Mweusi Karake.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, only 12 COMESA countries have so far confirmed
participation in the FTA which will be officially launched on
October 31 this year.
</P>
<P>
Karake also confirmed reports that Tanzania has finally pulled
out of the regional grouping.
</P>
<P>
"Unlike other countries which can ask for permission to suspend
their proceedings in the COMESA, Tanzania has not given any
official reason," Karake said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
