<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Petrol Prices to Go up in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Pump prices of petroleum
products are set to rise substantially in Kenya due to the
increased cost of crude oil and the depreciation of the Kenya
shilling, the East African Standard newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Officials in oil marketing firms were quoted by the paper as
saying the retail prices of super and regular petrol, diesel and
kerosene will go up by two to three shillings (about 0.038 U.S.
cents ) per liter, registering a 4 to 6 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
They attributed the increase to the rising crude oil price in
the international market from 27.55 dollars per barrel in July to
28.65 U.S. dollars in August.
</P>
<P>
Oil firms here adjust retail prices depending on changes in the
cost of crude oil, shilling-dollar exchange rate, taxation, cost
of transport and profit margins among other factors.
</P>
<P>
The officials said a hike is inevitable as the international
crude oil price had shot up by 1.10 dollars per barrel and the
exchange rate between shilling and dollar depreciated from 74
shillings to about 79 shillings last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
