<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon Maria kills 29 in southern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Typhoon Maria killed 47
people and caused at least 1.45 billion yuan (175 million US
dollars) worth of losses in two southern Chinese provinces, local
sources reported today.
</P>
<P>
In Guangdong, the economic powerhouse province bordering Hong
Kong, Maria killed 23 people and caused 1.28 billion yuan worth of
damage since it landed between the coastal cities of Huizhou and
Shanwei on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The typhoon also affected 3.74 million people and destroyed 7,
000 houses and damaged 122,000 hectares of farm land.
</P>
<P>
The disaster is now under control in the province.
Telecommunication service and power and water supply have all
resumed.
</P>
<P>
In neighboring Hunan province, Maria triggered landslides and
caused buildings to collapse, killing 24 people in the first two
days of this month.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary estimates by provincial authorities put economic
loss at 107 million yuan, with 43,850 hectares of cropland and 4,
500 homes destroyed in southern Hunan.
</P>
<P>
Over one million people in 183 towns and 14 cities and counties
in the province were affected by severe floods, which resulted
from the typhoon.
</P>
<P>
Typhoon Maria weakened into a tropical storm and faded after
rampaging through Guangdong and Hunan, meteorologists said.
</P>
</TEXT>
