<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Observers Pessimistic Over Soeharto's Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Observers and legal experts in
Indonesia expressed here Tuesday their pessimism over the trial
process against former president Soeharto, saying that Soeharto
might be found innocent.
</P>
<P>
Teten Masduki of the Indonesian Corruption Watch (ICW) told
reporters that," I am pessimistic that the trial will yield
positive result as we all have been waiting for. I am pessimistic
on the Soeharto's trial. I am not sure that he could be found
guilty. The indictments are too weak," he said.
</P>
<P>
Masduki said the 79-year old man should be charged in his
capacity as a (former) head of state instead of chairman of the
foundations.
</P>
<P>
"Because if Soeharto is charged in his capacity as chairman of
the foundations there were no evidences that he broke law," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He should have been charged in his capacity as a (former)
president who has abused his power by issuing the government
decrees and regulations to enrich his own family and cronies,
Masduki added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Gaguk Subagyanto, a former prosecutor at the
Attorney General Office regretted at the indictments. "That is a
sad indictments,"Subagyanto said, referring to the indictments
against Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Separately, Minister of Law and Human Right Affairs Yusril Ihza
Mahendra refused to comment on the trial process against the
former president.
</P>
<P>
"The government will not intervene in such a process," the
minister told reporters at the parliament building.
</P>
<P>
But, earlier he also expressed his pessimism if Soeharto could
be found guilty as the former president, who ran the country for
more than three decades with an iron hand, was only charged with
corruption in his capacity as the chairman of foundations.
</P>
<P>
The former five stars general has been charged by state
prosecutors with allegedly misusing some 1.4 trillion rupiah (155
million U.S.dollars) and 416 million U.S. dollars of state funds
that had gone to his seven tax-free charity foundations.
</P>
<P>
He is principally charged with violating article 1(a) of
corruption law No.3/1973 and he is also subject to a subsidiary
charge under article 1 (b) of the same law with abuse of power
which causes losses to the state.
</P>
<P>
"It is hard to prove that Soeharto has done a corruption crime
if he was charged in his capacity as the foundations chairman
because under the foundations statutes, Soeharto has rights to
distribute the foundation's funds. He did no crime in this matter,
" Frans Hendra Winata, a member of the National Law Commission
said.
</P>
<P>
"But there has been no changes for the prosecutors to revise
their indictments as such things have been filed to the court and
the session itself has been taking place," he said.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto's trial began on Thursday, August 31 with the absence
of the defendant due to medical reasons.
</P>
<P>
Chief judge Lalu Mariyun then decided to adjourn the trial
until Mid-September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
