<HEADLINE> Xinhua Asia-Pacific Economic News Summary, Tuesday, September 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Southeast Asian motorcycle sales demonstrated a
strong recovery to increase 54.3 percent in the first seven months
on a year-on-year basis, according to a report from Honda Motor
Company's regional headquarters here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Total sales in the Southeast Asian market during the January-to-
July period recorded at 1.15 million units, with Thailand
maintaining its position as the region's largest motorcycle market,
followed by Indonesia, Malaysia and the Philippines, it said.
</P>
<P>
The regional sales have peaked in 1997 with total sales of 3.3
million units, but severely decreased in 1998 and 1999 due to the
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- The share by foreign investors in South Korea's gross
domestic product (GDP) hit 7.8 percent in 1999, up from 2.6
percent in 1996, the South Korean Maeil Business Newspaper said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said foreigner investors are responsible for 30-
percent of the local stock market's capitalization and their
contribution to the economy has been on a steady rise.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government said the ratio of foreign
investments against GDP remain at a low level, compared with the
worldwide average of 11.7 percent in the same year.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Commerce, Industry and Energy wishes to raise
the GDP portion of foreign investments to around 20 percent, said
the paper.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea's machine exports to Southeast Asian
nations rose 20 percent in July from last year to 11.6 billion U.S.
dollars, the Korea Trade-Investment Promotion Agency said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The rise came from boosted exports of semiconductor
manufacturing equipment, machine tools and fabric processing
appliances due to economic recovery and the establishment of
industrial infrastructures in the southeast Asian region.
</P>
<P>
Singapore, Malaysia, Vietnam and Thailand all increased imports
by more than 20 percent in the first half of the year from the
same period last year, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
ZHUHAI -- Kusatsu Electric Co., Ltd. of Japan Monday started a
business in the city of Zhuhai in south China's Guangdong Province
to produce motors for home appliances with an investment of 12
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the manufacturing venture will be
situated inside Qingwan Industrial Zone of Zhuhai, one of China's
four earliest special economic zones.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The Philippine peso ended weaker on a 32-month low
Monday against the U.S. dollar amid higher demand for the
greenback.
</P>
<P>
The peso closed at 45.30 pesos to one dollar, 15 centavos
weaker from last Friday's close of 45.15 pesos.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said there is high demand for dollars, as import
requirements of local manufacturers have started picking up.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnam is striving to raise the number of telephone
subscribers to 3 million by the end of this month, Vietnam News
Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam had 2.95 million telephone subscribers by the end of
August or approximately four telephones per 100 people, according
to the Vietnam Post and Telecommunications Corporation (VNPT).
</P>
<P>
Vietnam plans to gain a year-on-year increase of 80 percent in
telephone expansion as it installs 18,000-20,000 telephones per
week.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Ten supervisory groups, headed by directors of the
State Forestry Administration (SFA), have been sent all over China
to oversee nearly 50 major cases of illegal logging, woodland
abuse and poaching of endangered animals.
</P>
<P>
These cases are among the 500,000 similar cases reported
throughout China in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The campaign is a major step by the administration to conform
with the central government's strategy of achieving sustainable
development of China's western regions.
</P>
<P>
The administration blamed local officials and authorities, who
are often tempted by short-term economic gains from illegal timber
businesses, for a large number of forest-related problems, the
English-language newspaper claimed.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
MACAO -- The government of China's Macao Special Administrative
Region (SAR) will buy a large amount of computer software from
Microsoft at rather favorable prices, the Macao Daily News
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The software will have a market value of more than 10 million
patacas (1.25 million U.S. dollars). As a result, 44 government
departments will have their software upgraded or begin to use
authorized software in the coming two years.
</P>
<P>
In view of the mass purchase, Microsoft will offer a 35-percent
discount at least.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan and Russia issued 15 documents on agreements for
expanding bilateral cooperation Tuesday, the final day of Russian
President Vladimir Putin's three-day official visit to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Prominent among the documents are a joint statement on
cooperation on international issues, a new program on economic
cooperation, and an agreement for promoting joint economic
activities on four disputed Russian-held islands off Japan's
northernmost prefecture of Hokkaido.
</P>
<P>
On the joint economic activities on the disputed islands, the
two leaders agreed to accelerate expert-level talks toward
realizing a marine farm for sea urchins and shellfish.
</P>
<P>
The new program also reiterated Japan's support for Russia's
bid to join the World Trade Organization and offers technical
assistance to that end.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
