<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soeharto's City Arrest Status Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesia's South Jakarta
District Court extended here Tuesday the city arrest status
against former president Soeharto for 60 days, as of September 7.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the district court, Lalu Mariyun said the extension
was aimed at giving judges more time and chance to verify the
state of health condition of the 79-year-old man who failed to
appear before the initial hearing on August 31.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto failed to attend the trial at that time, according to
his lawyers, due to medical reasons.
</P>
<P>
Mariyun also said that the move is intended to give time for
prosecutors to complete the dossiers of the former strongman.
</P>
<P>
The South Jakarta District Court is in charge of trying the
former ruler. It will resume the trial again in Mid-September to
hear reports from Soeharto's medical team on the health condition
of the former president who was forced to step down in May two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto's city arrest firstly was imposed on August 9,
following the imposition of the house arrest on him. But Soeharto'
s house arrest status has expired on August 10, after three times
of extension.
</P>
<P>
Mariyun, who is also chief judge for Soeharto's trial, added
that his side has formed an independent medical team to reassess
the Soeharto's health condition.
</P>
<P>
The team consists of medical experts and doctors from some
reputable universities in the country such as the University of
Indonesia Jakarta, the Gadjah Mada University Yogyakarta and the
Airlangga University Surabaya.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua tried to contact Soeharto's lawyers, Juan Felix
Tampubolon and Mohamad Assegaf, to get confirmation on the 79-year-
old man's city arrest status extension, but the two were not
available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
