<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Launches Initiative to Boost Employability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Singapore announced Tuesday
an initiative to enhance the employability of workers and ensure
that every industry has a responsive system to upgrade skills.
</P>
<P>
The National Skills Recognition System (NSRS) will define
current competence of workers and encourage skills improvement
through byte-sized modules at training centers established by each
sector.
</P>
<P>
The initiative is targeted at some 500,000 workers with only
secondary education, those who made up about one-third of
Singapore's workforce and yet the most vulnerable to retrenchment.
</P>
<P>
The initial target is to establish 1,000 skills standards in
100 key industries and to certify 300,000 workers by 2005.
</P>
<P>
With the system, the Ministry of Manpower and the Productivity
and Standards Board aim to develop 1,000 skills standards in 100
industries.
</P>
<P>
About 166 million Singapore dollars (about 97 million U.S.
dollars ) have been set aside to implement the initiative over
five years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a pilot implementation of the skills recognition
system was conducted in three sectors - hotel, marine and cleaning
- in which 27 companies attended between March last year and April
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
