<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Newspaper Hails Arab Warning over Jerusalem Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A leading newspaper in the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) Tuesday hailed a strongly-worded warning
that Arab countries will collectively rupture relations with any
country that moves its embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The warning, issued Monday at the conclusion of a two-day
meeting of Arab League foreign ministers council in Cairo, is "the
most positive and strongest decision ever taken by the Arabs on the
Jerusalem issue," said the Arabic-language daily Al Ittihad.
</P>
<P>
The state-run newspaper said that such a warning coincided with
the assurance given by the ministerial meeting that Jerusalem is
the key to the Arab-Israeli peacemaking, and that peace will not be
achieved without a fair and logical solution based on international
legitimacy, even if negotiations take decades.
</P>
<P>
"The Arab stance expressed by the Arab League Ministerial
Council comes after a long silence by the Arab countries, an issue
which created some doubts about Arab public opinion towards the
stance of the Arab governments," noted the paper.
</P>
<P>
"This was especially when Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
became subject to tremendous pressures at Camp David, which
compelled him to ask for support and back up from Arab and Islamic
countries," the paper pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"From now onwards, we should employ this stance as a cornerstone
for any Arab and Islamic movement dealing with the issue of
Jerusalem and Al Aqsa mosque, where our stance should be summarized
as no peace without Jerusalem," the paper concluded.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied East Jerusalem in the 1967 Mideast War and later
declared the whole of the city its "eternal and indivisible
capital," a claim the international community has never recognized.
The Arabs are insisting on Palestinian sovereignty over the eastern
sector of Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
