<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Increase Mombasa Port's Handling Capacity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Ports Authority (KPA)
has unveiled plans for expanding Mombasa Port's handling capacity
to at least 10 million tons of cargoes by 2020, reported the East
African weekly available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the authority managing director Brown Ondego, KPA
will also increase its container handling capacity to 910,000
twenty-foot equivalent units (TEU) by 2020.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Mombasa Port in southeastern Kenya now
handles some 8 million tons of cargoes and 248,000 TEUs annually
and it is the gateway for imports and exports of some African
inland countries such as Uganda, Rwanda and Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Ondego made the remarks at a recent investment sensitization
seminar for councilors and senior officials of the Mombasa
municipal council.
</P>
<P>
He said KPA's vision is to make Mombasa a world class port in
the delivery of services and promote it as the primary gateway to
East Africa's hinterland, and restore and maintain a clean and
safe environment.
</P>
<P>
Ondego noted that his authority will continue to contact and
coordinate with port users and other organizations involved in the
port operations like shipping agencies and clearing and forwarding
firms.
</P>
<P>
"For overall improvement of all port services and for better
utilization of resources, the government has recognized there is
need to commercialize some of the port's facilities and services,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Govt Urged to Privatize Commercial Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan parliamentary
committee on
finance has proposed that the Uganda Commercial Bank Limited (UCBL)
should be sold within six months or be entrusted to a private
management firm, the New Vision reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a report presented to the House Monday, the committee said
it was irregular for the Bank of Uganda (BOU) to act as the
regulator and manager of UCBL at the same time for two years.
</P>
<P>
"For a regulator to be a manager of a commercial bank for such
a time is irregular, since it will be liable in case anything goes
wrong in that commercial bank," said the report.
</P>
<P>
If UCBL is not privatized within the next six months, BOU
should enter into an independent management contract for private
management of UCBL, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Parliament members said the government should present a report
to the House on the state of the UCBL under the management of BOU.
</P>
</TEXT>
