<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worsening Environment Calls for Sustained Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The heads of state and
government across the world are gathering in the U.N. headquarters
in New York this week to discuss the major challenges facing the
whole mankind in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
One of the challenges they will debate on is the deteriorating
environment and the strategy of sustained development.
</P>
<P>
The unprecedented development over the past few hundred years
has resulted in the most brilliant civilization of today. But the
price is dear: global warming, water shortage, spreading
desertification and disappearing bio-diversity. The homeland of
mankind is losing its fertility and beauty, a bitter fruit borne
out of an unsustainable way of human activity.
</P>
<P>
In the 20th century, half of the earth's wetlands were
destroyed and an equally half of the rivers across the world were
polluted. During the last quarter of the century, the per capita
fresh water supply declined by 30 percent and desertification
ruined or threatened to ruin the life of nearly 1 billion people
in more than 100 countries.
</P>
<P>
The global bio-diversity decreased by 30 percent in the past
three decades. In addition, more than 30 percent of the mammals,
over 10 percent of foliage species and 10 percent of plant species
are in danger of extinction. The forest is disappearing at a speed
of 16 million hectares a year.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Environment Program, in its Global
Environment Outlook 2000 last September, says that as global
efforts in tackling major environment issues are outpaced by
environment deterioration, the human race is progressing on the
path of unsustained development and that the issue of environment
is one of the most severe challenges the humankind faces in the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The very fact that the Millennium Summit slated for September 6-
8 has treated the environment problem as one of the most pressing
global issues fully demonstrates the importance the entire world
has attached to the issue.
</P>
<P>
The mankind has only one earth and should not act in an
arrogant way as to violate the law of nature.
</P>
<P>
The experience drawn from environment protection has provided
us with a significant reference: respect for the nature, seeking
harmony between man and nature, changing the pattern of excessive
consumption, exploring a global economic system accommodating the
environment, concerted efforts by all countries with developed
nations bearing more responsibility in enviorenment protection.
</P>
<P>
Developed countries are the major contributors to such global
issues as environment pollution and irrational and unjust
international and economic orders, the main consumers of natural
resources and the largest beneficiaries of the progress of human
civilization.
</P>
<P>
So they are liable to shoulder greater responsibility than
developing countries to meet the new challenges.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, developing countries should draw lessons from
the experience of developed countries in economic development and
strive to take a path of sustained development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
