<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, September 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin arrived here this
evening to participate in the Millennium summit of the United
Nations (U.N.) scheduled from September 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang was warmly greeted at the airport by the
resident Chinese officials and hundreds of overseas Chinese and
Chinese Americans at the Waldorf-Astorial hotel, where Jiang will
stay.
</P>
<P>
During the event, the Chinese president will also attend the
summit of the U.N. Security Council and deliver a speech on issues
such as maintaining world peace and security. (UN-Jiang Arrival)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. presidential campaign entered a pivotal
stage as Republican and Democratic nominees kicked off their fall
campaign on Labor Day Monday.
</P>
<P>
Republican presidential candidate, Texas Governor George W.
Bush, started his fall campaign with a week-long tour through
swing states. His trip will take him to nine cities in Illinois,
Michigan, Pennsylvania, Wisconsin, Indiana and Ohio, the states
that have 107 electoral votes up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
His multi-state campaign will focus on medicare, economy, taxes,
defense and social security, his aides said.
</P>
<P>
Bush and his running mate, former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney,
arrived in a Chicago suburb early Monday to take part in the Labor
Day parade. (US-Presidential Campaign)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan and Russia issued 15 documents on agreements for
expanding bilateral cooperation Tuesday, the final day of Russian
President Vladimir Putin's three-day official visit to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Prominent among the documents are a joint statement on
cooperation on international issues, a new program on economic
cooperation, and an agreement for promoting joint economic
activities on four disputed Russian-held islands off Japan's
northernmost prefecture of Hokkaido. (Japan-Russia-Cooperation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Bernard Kouchner, the head of Kosovo's U.N.
administration, announced Monday in the Kosovo capital Pristina
that the U.N. police director of the jail in Kosovska Mitrovica
was suspended after prisoners escaped late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported that the officer comes
from a central-America country.
</P>
<P>
Late Sunday, 15 Serb prisoners escaped from the jail and two of
them were recaptured immediately, but 13 others remain at large,
the report said. (Kosovo-UN-Jail Escape)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Visiting Russian President Vladimir Putin and Japanese
Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori failed to make substantive progress on
concluding a peace treaty after ending their summit in Tokyo
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders, in a statement issued shortly after their
third round of talks Tuesday morning, confirmed negotiations on
the treaty will continue.
</P>
<P>
Putin and Mori "agreed to continue negotiations on concluding a
peace treaty while resolving" a territorial dispute blocking the
pact, the statement said. (Japan-Russia-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- Hundreds of Queensland university students in
Australia plan to join protesters during the World Economic Forum
scheduled for next week.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported Tuesday that
spokeswoman Liz Shield said students were caught up in economic
globalization as universities increasingly sought sponsorships
from corporations.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of protesters are expected to mass outside the forum
which opens at Melbourne's Crown Casino next Monday. (Australia-
Student-Protest) 
</P>
