<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge in Tokyo, Nikkei Closes Below 16,500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices plunged in Tokyo
Tuesday as investors remained reluctant to buy stocks in the
absence of fresh incentives, with the benchmark Nikkei index
closing below 16,500 for the first time in nine trading days.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 235.94 points, or 1.41
percent from Monday's close to end at 16,452.27, falling for the
sixth straight trading day.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, declined 11.36 points or 0.76 percent to 1,
491.04.
</P>
<P>
Corporations continued to sell cross-held shares ahead of the
midyear book-closing this month, leading overall share prices
lower, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section edged up to 528.24 million shares
from Monday's 500.5 million.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi Cable Industries was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
The drug, wholesale and insurance sectors were down, while
semiconductor makers continued to face selling, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the rubber, oil, marine transportation and retail
sectors were firm.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainsers 772 to 473, with 170 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
