<HEADLINE> S. Korea Vows to Grab More Gold Medals At Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean delegation to
the Sydney Olympics Tuesday vowed to secure at least the 10th
place of the Games' gold medal table.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony to launch the delegation Tuesday afternoon here,
398 delegates, including 284 players and 114 coaches and staff,
gathered in dwontown Seoul.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Prime Minister Lee Han-dong, Culture and Tourism
Minister Park Jie-won and South Korean Olympic Committee President
Kim Un-yong attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the team, Lee said the Olympic Games are a war
without shots and frontline of a battle to show national
competitive power.
</P>
<P>
He called on the delegates to inspire the South Korean people
and enhance national prestige by winning more medals than before.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also said the Sydney Olympics carry a
special meaning to us now that we are opening a new chapter in our
history with momentum building from the June inter-Korean summit.
</P>
<P>
He urged all South Korean athletes to show the world that the
two sides of the Korean Peninsular are now reconciling and
cooperating with each other and to compete with good will.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of 216 South Korean Olympians will leave for
Sydney Friday and the others will leave in groups before they all
reunite in Sydney on September 13, two days before the Games'
opening ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
