<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak indicated to U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan in a meeting at the United Nations on Monday
that he will give the peace process another "few weeks" before
turning his attention elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Prior to this meeting, a senior source in the Prime Minister's
Office said that Barak will give the current round of the peace
process until the middle of October to run its course, after which
he will turn inward and try to restructure his government and
reconstitute a Knesset (parliament) majority.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister and Defense Minister Ehud Barak has
rejected the request of Chief of Staff Shaul Mofaz for a real-term
increase of a billion shekels (about 250 million U.S. dollars) in
the Israeli Defense Forces' budget for 2001.
</P>
<P>
The main beneficiary of this decision will be the education
budget, including higher education.
</P>
<P>
The IDF based its request on a compromise from Barak that he
would restore the billion shekels that were cut in this year's
budget. The defense budget for 2001 will be 36.3 billion shekels
(about 9 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak arrived in New York on
Monday to attend the U.N. Millennium Summit and also to meet with
U.S. President Bill Clinton and Palestinian National Authority
Chairman Yasser Arafat in an effort to break the impasse in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Barak has slightly relaxed his pressure campaign against Arafat.
After trying to raise expectations about this week's meeting in New
York and describing it as the decisive point in the peace process,
Barak spoke on Monday about another "few weeks," at the end of
which Israel will know whether it has a "partner of peace."
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Communications Minister Binyamin Ben-Eliezer put an
end to the monopoly of domestic telecommunications by the major
telecommunications company of Bezeq on Monday by signing
regulations that open the market to competition and allow for the
introduction of few Internet access.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Eliezer's decision follows the introduction of competition
in international phone calls, cell-phones, and multiple-channel
television broadcasting, and Ben-Eliezer said he was sure that the
public will reap the benefits of better service and lower prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
