<HEADLINE> Pastoralists in Northwest Kenya to Graze in Northeast Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan Turkana and Ugandan
Karimojong pastoralists have negotiated a peace settlement,
allowing the Turkana to graze in Uganda's northeastern region of
Karamoja.
</P>
<P>
The New Vision daily reported Tuesday that the agreement was
reached at a meeting Saturday and was witnessed by a 40-man
delegation from the Kenyan government and Turkana elders.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, held in Kalapata Dodoth county in Kotido district,
gave grazing rights to the Turkana in northwest Kenya outside the
Kidepo National Game Park in Karamoja.
</P>
<P>
The agreement ends 29 years of hostility between the Turkana
and the three Karimojong clans of the Dodoth, the Jie and the
Matheniko, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan delegation was led by the Turkana district
commissioner Peter Mooke, and the Ugandan delegation headed by
Kotido district council leader Drani Dradiga. 
</P>
</TEXT>
