<HEADLINE> New Zealand Finds Another Snake Imported from Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Snake-free New Zealand has
found a juvenile Australian Eastern Small-Eyed snake.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry said in a
press release here Tuesday that the 30 centimeter-long snake was
found alive on Sunday when a shipping container of used vehicle
batteries from Australia was being unloaded into an industrial
building in the suburb of Petone, Wellington Region.
</P>
<P>
The snake, common to the East Coast of Australia, would have
been able to survive in New Zealand conditions, it said.
</P>
<P>
The snake was killed and the area where it was found is being
searched as a precautionary matter, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The snake find comes after New Zealand Minister for Biosecurity
Marian Hobbs announced in April an increased level of inspection
on cargo coming from "high risk" countries. The minister's
announcement followed the unprecedented discovery of three snakes
over a period of three weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
