<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Exports Hit Record High In July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka recorded in July
this year the highest-ever export earnings for a single month
during the past five years, reaching 570 million U.S. dollars, the
Central Bank said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The exports "recorded an impressive growth of 35 percent
compared with July 1999," said the bank in a statement. The higher
growth in exports in July resulted in a trade surplus of 13
million dollars, the first trade surplus since September 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the export sector continued to
improve during the first seven months of 2000, maintaining the
growth momentum achieved in late 1999.
</P>
<P>
Export earnings from January to July 2000 increased by 22
percent, reflecting the continued growth in textiles and garments,
rubber-based products, fish products, gems, diamonds, jewelry and
tea.
</P>
<P>
Expenditure on imports increased by 18 percent to 557 million
dollars, reflecting a growth in intermediate and investment goods.
</P>
<P>
All major categories of imports grew in July 2000. However,
food imports declined by 16 percent due to lower imports of rice,
flour, sugar, wheat and milk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
