<HEADLINE> Tension Reappears Along Thai-Lao Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Tension reappeared along the
Thai-Lao border since Lao militia was deployed on three yet-to-be-
demarcated islets in the Mekong River off the Chiang Saen district,
Chiang Rai Province, 785 kilometers north of Bangkok, The Bangkok
Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chiang Rai Governor Samrerng Boonyopakorn was quoted as saying
that since last week, about 30 Lao militiamen from Bo Keo Province
in the Lao side have been deployed on the three islets of Koh Mano
1, Koh Mano 2 and Koh Pha Kham in the border river of Mekong.
</P>
<P>
Koh Mano 1 and 2 are about 100 meters from the Thai bank of the
river and Koh Pha Kham 50 meters.
</P>
<P>
The presence of the Lao unit has prevented some 60 Thai
families who have long planted maize there from entering the
islets, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Local officials had received a letter from Laos saying Thai
villagers could harvest crops on the islets until September 15.
</P>
<P>
To ease the tension, Thailand has invited Lao provincial
governors to Friday's meeting of the Thai-Lao border committee to
discuss the issue, the English language newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Security measures have been enhanced along the border since
July 3,when more than 100 Lao rebels attacked a Lao customs
checkpoint across the Sirindhorn district in the Thai border
province of Ubon Rachathani, 629 kilometers northeast of Bangkok.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
