<HEADLINE> Air Tragedy Investigation Blocked by Fog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Fog and smoke blocked the
security experts investigating the crash of a light plane in
Queensland, northeast Australia.
</P>
<P>
A Queensland police spokesman was quoted by the Australian
Associated Press as saying their helicopter could not land due to
fog and smoke from a bushfire ignited by the crash.
</P>
<P>
The twin-engine light plane with seven gold miners and one
pilot on board crashed Tuesday morning in a remote area in
Queensland.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that all the eight on board may have died in
the crash which took place shortly after the plane took off from
Perth last night when the cabin depressurized. The plane had flown
on automatic pilot for four hours, covering almost 3,000
kilometers across three states before the crash.
</P>
<P>
A number of police experts managed to get to the crash site in
dry and rugged bushland.
</P>
<P>
"The debris is fairly well scattered and it appears the
aircraft hit at quite a speed," the spokesman said. 
</P>
