<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Streamline Educational Administration Agencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will merge its three
educational administration agencies into a new ministry in 2002,
in line with the education reform policy, The Bangkok Post
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Vijit Srisa-arn, chairman of the Education Reform Commission,
was quoted as saying the Education Ministry, the University
Affairs Ministry and the Office of the National Education
Commission will be merged into a proposed national education
ministry.
</P>
<P>
The plan, aimed at decentralizing power, will also help reduce
education management costs by 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Vijit said a public hearing will be held this month to gauge
public opinion. The findings will be submitted to the cabinet by
March or April next year.
</P>
<P>
A member of the Education Reform Commission said officials from
some dissolved educational units in those agencies would be sent
to work in local schools.
</P>
<P>
A committee will be set up to place officials in vacant slots
based on their qualifications and working experiences.
</P>
<P>
Budgets will be allocated directly to schools, which will be
given a free hand in managing their funds and developing the
potential of their personnel.
</P>
<P>
Education units will be responsible for transferring and
promoting teaching personnel in areas under their jurisdiction.
However, they will not be authorized to expel teachers and school
administrators.
</P>
<P>
The National Education Committee will have the sole power to
expel teaching personnel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
