<HEADLINE> Pinochet Calls for Generosity Toward Past </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This is the first public speech of the former lifetime senator
since August 8 when the Chilean Supreme Court revoked his
parliamentary immunity and thus paved the way for the former
leader to stand trial on 170 charges against him.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, read by his granddaughter Maria Jose Martinez in
his house at Dehesa, the retired general said he cherished the
hope that the disagreement and the pain of yesterday will be
overcome.
</P>
<P>
The former paramount leader of the South American country said
that unity is necessary for the next generation because they need
a generous attitude to settle the previous conflict and contribute
to peace and progress.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, who accompanied his granddaughter in her reading,
did not answer any question of reporters. His lawyer Fernando
Barros told reporters that by issuing the letter, Pinochet wants
to call for respect of the pain suffered by numerous Chileans in
the past.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, more than 3,000 people died
or disappeared and tens of thousand fled the country during
Pinochet's reign from 1973 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, 84, returned to Chile in early March after 503 days
under house arrest in Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
