<HEADLINE> China Launches Project to Ease Water Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 5 (Xinhua) -- China has launched a project
to divert water from the Yellow River to Tianjin in north China to
ease the city's acute water shortage, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The project, which was scheduled to be finished in early
November, will have the capacity to supply the city with 40
billion cubic meters of water per annum, a water resources
official surnamed Liu was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Water from the Yellow River will travel 440 kilometers from the
Weishan Gate of Donge County in east China's Shandong Province, to
reach Tianjin's Qiuxuan Gate, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
This is the sixth time that Tianjin has used water from the
Yellow River since the first diverting in 1972.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin has suffered water shortage since 1997, when severe
droughts hit the city, and the daily water supply has dropped to
less than 1.7 million cubic meters from more than two million
cubic meters, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin also resorted to other channels to ease its water
tension. Water from Hebei Province's Panjiakou Reservoir, more
than 300 kilometers northeast to Tianjin, was diverted into the
city on August 27.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
