<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Inflation to Exceed 7 Percent in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
estimated that the country's inflation will exceed the 7-percent
level for 2000 instead of the assumed target of 5-7 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The government's plan to reduce the fuel subsidy in October
2000 plus the holidays in December will likely set the inflation
higher than 7 percent," The Indonesian Observer daily Tuesday
quoted Finance Minister Prijadi Prapto Suhardjo as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the inflation rate from January to August 2000 reached
4.71 percent while the inflation rate in August was recorded at 0.
51 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the local currency's exchange rate, the newly-appointed
minister said that although the rupiah managed to strengthen to
the 8,200-8,300 per U.S. dollar level at the end of August, it is
still difficult to predict movements in the national currency.
</P>
<P>
This is because fluctuations in the rupiah is more affected by
non-economic factors, such as the vulnerable socio-political and
security stability, he added.
</P>
<P>
Prijadi also projected a deficit of between 3.5 and 3.9 percent
of the gross domestic product in the 2000 budget, compared with
the 4.8 percent targeted in the budget.
</P>
<P>
According to Prijadi, the expected improvement was due to
higher crude oil prices and lower government expenses.
</P>
<P>
The 2000 fiscal year covers a truncated April to end-December
period because Indonesia is aligning its fiscal year with the
calendar year from the previous April-March system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
