<HEADLINE> 17 Still Missing After Ship Sinks in Maluku, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian rescuers continued
to search for survivors of a ship which carried 43 passengers and
crew and capsized in bad weather off Maluku islands, Indonesia,
according to The Indonesian Observer Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Major Hendri Suprianto as saying 17 people
from the coastal freighter, the Mulya Star, were still unaccounted
for.
</P>
<P>
So far, 23 survivors have been picked up from the water along
with three bodies, the naval officer said.
</P>
<P>
The Mulya Star was on its way from Seram island in Maluku to
Probolinggo, a port in East Java. It sank off the Manipa strait
near Ambon, capital of Maluku Province, on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Suprianto said three warships, a Nomad maritime surveillance
aircraft and a number of fishing boats were still searching for
survivors.
</P>
<P>
In July, a ferry carrying more than 500 Christian refugees and
crew sank near the Malukus. The passengers were fleeing the strife-
torn archipelago after their villages on Halmahera island in North
Maluku were destroyed in communal clashes. 
</P>
