<HEADLINE> Regional Anti-Racism Seminar Opens in Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 5 (Xinhua) -- A regional seminar on racism,
human rights of migrants and human trafficking is to open here
Tuesday at the headquarters of the U.N. Economic and Social
Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP).
</P>
<P>
Jointly sponsored by the ESCAP and the Office of the U.N.High
Commissioner for Human Rights, the September 5-7 meeting is part
of a series of four regional meetings being held in preparation
for the upcoming Third World Anti-Racism Conference in South
Africa later this month.
</P>
<P>
Deputy U.N. High Commissioner for Human Rights Bertrand
Ramcharan and ESCAP Human Rights chief official Nibhon Debavalya
will give opening speeches at the seminar.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day seminar, experts on racism, human rights
and migration in the Asia-Pacific region will discuss issues
related to racism and human rights, exchange information on "best
practices" in dealing with racism, debate on action-oriented
strategies and forge support for the World Anti-Racism Conference.
</P>
<P>
The South Africa conference, decided in the United Nations
General Assembly's resolution 51/111, "will be action-oriented and
focus on practical measures to eradicate racism, including
measures of prevention, education and protection through the
provision of effective remedies." 
</P>
</TEXT>
