<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Guerrillas Attack Oil Pipelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Three oil pipelines in Colombia,
which export more than 200,000 barrels of oil daily, are out of
service due to guerrilla sabotage, said the state-owned oil
company Ecopetrol.
</P>
<P>
The most seriously affected pipeline, the Cano Limon-Covel
pipeline, which once pumped 105,000 barrels of oil daily, has
operated only 80 hours since July 23 because of 24 dynamite
attacks by the National Liberation Army (ELN) and the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC).
</P>
<P>
Ecopetrol said it had to stop foreign sales of oil produced in
the Cano Limon-Covel field, which is located on the border with
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
The municipalities in the oil-producing zone have experienced
more than 126 million dollars in losses as a direct result of the
sabotage, it said.
</P>
<P>
The ELN, the second largest guerrilla group in Colombia, has
been conducting attacks against the 780-kilometer Cano Limon-
Covenas pipeline since 1986 in an effort to exert pressure against
foreign oil companies and force them to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
While FARC, the largest and oldest guerrilla army in Colombia,
attacks the pipelines sporadically as part of its ongoing military
objectives.
</P>
<P>
Oil is the main product of the Colombian economy. Export income
for this year was forecast at nearly 5 billion dollars, a goal
that probably will not be met due to guerrilla sabotage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: U.S. Presidential Campaign Heats Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. presidential
campaign entered a pivotal stage as Republican and Democratic
nominees kicked off their fall campaign on Labor Day Monday.
</P>
<P>
Republican presidential candidate, Texas Governor George W.
Bush, started his fall campaign with a week-long tour through
swing states. His trip will take him to nine cities in Illinois,
Michigan, Pennsylvania, Wisconsin, Indiana and Ohio, the states
that have 107 electoral votes up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
His multi-state campaign will focus on medicare, economy, taxes,
defense and social security, his aides said.
</P>
<P>
Bush and his running mate, former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney,
arrived in a Chicago suburb early Monday to take part in the Labor
Day parade.
</P>
<P>
"As we come down to the stretch, we're ready for the contest.
We feel great about our chances," Bush said during a rally in
Naperville, Illinois.
</P>
<P>
"The surplus doesn't exist because of the ingenuity and hard
work of the federal government. The surplus exists because of the
ingenuity and hard work of the American working people," he said.
</P>
<P>
While Bush touted his 10-year, 1.3 trillion dollar tax-cut plan
in Illinois Monday, his Democratic rival, Vice President Al Gore
continued his 27-hour non-stop campaign blitz designed to reach
out to core Democratic supporters.
</P>
<P>
Gore, in his speech to steelworkers in Pittsburgh Monday,
renewed his pledge to raise the minimum wage, build more public
schools, secure passage of a patients' bill of rights, and provide
prescription drug coverage for seniors.
</P>
<P>
"What it all comes down to is whether or not we're going to
fight for those who most need the help," he said.
</P>
<P>
Gore's marathon campaign trip around Labor Day includes a
meeting with construction workers in Pennsylvania, exchange of
greetings with autoworkers and hospital employees in Michigan, a
breakfast with firefighters in Florida, and a rally at an outdoor
motor speedway in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
Labor Day is seen as the traditional start of the fall campaign
as many Americans will start to pay attention to the presidential
race after the holiday.
</P>
<P>
Polls show Bush and Gore neck-and-neck in most of the states,
therefore millions of independent voters who tend to swing between
the two major parties will probably decide the election.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said this year's election might be the closest contest
in more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
So far, Bush and Gore have not yet agreed on the timetable and
venues of the presidential debates before the November 7 election.
</P>
<P>
Gore's campaign rejected Bush's offer on Sunday to participate
in three presidential debates, including one on September 12
during a special prime-time edition of NBC's "Meet the Press."
</P>
<P>
Bush also offered to hold a debate on October 3 in Los Angeles
on CNN's "Larry King Live" and another one on October 17 at
Washington University in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
Gore, instead, insisted that Bush should first accept the three
90-minute debates proposed by the Commission on Presidential
Debates.
</P>
<P>
"This is not about what is best for George W. Bush or what is
best for Al Gore. It's about what's best for the American people,"
said Gore Monday. He has already accepted the commission's offers
for three 90-minute debates.
</P>
<P>
Gore maintains that the three events proposed by the commission
will reach the widest audience, while what Bush has proposed will
not.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Shuttlers Get Other Training Facility in Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Olympic badminton
players will benefit from a special training facility near the
Games athletes' village at Homebush Bay in Sydney, Australia, the
Jakarta Post reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's Olympic training director Arie Sudewo said the
Indonesian community in Sydney invited the players to train in the
sports hall in a high school near the athletes' village. The hall
is a 30-minute walk from the athletes' village.
</P>
<P>
"The Indonesian community, mostly consisting of people from
West Sumatra, have asked the shuttlers to practice in the sports
hall. The community has a badminton club and they regularly rent
the sports hall to practice. Our shuttlers will no longer have to
depend on the practice facility provided by the (Games) organizers,
" Arie was quoted by the newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nineteen men's and women's players and eight coaches and
officials will be part of the last batch of the Indonesian Olympic
contingent leaving for Sydney on Sunday, targeting two gold medals
at the Olympic Games. 
