<HEADLINE> Graham Predicts Chaos over Transfer Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Tottenham Hotspur manager
George Graham predicted chaos on Monday while officials of soccer'
s world governing body FIFA wait to find out if the transfer
system is to be abolished.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission wants to abolish transfer fees and
binding contracts, which they think are restrictive.
</P>
<P>
FIFA president Sepp Blatter called last week for transfer fees
to be abolished for players aged over 24, but for compensation
payments to be made for players aged 18 to 24.
</P>
<P>
Graham had paid a club record 11 million pounds (16.09 million
U.S dollars) for 26-year-old Ukrainian star Sergei Rebrov. He
felt the current situation unacceptable. "No-one knows what route
FIFA and UEFA will go down but this situation cannot be good for
the game -- it will leave it in chaos," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There's a lot of speculation about what will happen but one
thing is for sure -- the days of spending vast sums of money on
transfers have gone now. I can't see any more big transfers
taking place while there is all this uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
"Some clubs in European competition might be prepared to take
a chance on four million or five million pound (5.8 or 8.6 million
U.S. dollars) players to strengthen their squads but that is
hardly big money nowadays. But everyone else will be sitting
tight to see what happens."  
</P>
</TEXT>
