<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diamond Countries to Adopt Certification System  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 JOHANNESBURG, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Officials of diamond
producing countries,
</P>
<P>
investigating how to stop the sale of diamonds from war zones,
will propose a system of international certification, a Namibian
official said Tuesday after a meeting on "conflict diamonds".
</P>
<P>
Another proposal, to etch legitimate diamonds with laser
markings, was simply too complex and expensive, said Kennedy
Hamutenya, Namibia's director of mines and acting diamond
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to come up with a simple process that can be
easily implemented by all countries concerned," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hamutenya was speaking ahead of a conference in South Africa
later this month where ministers from diamond-producing countries
are expected to formally adopt measures to outlaw conflict
diamonds.
</P>
<P>
The proposals had been debated at meetings in South Africa,
Angola and London over the past four months, Hamutenya said.
</P>
<P>
 He said these measures would then be forwarded to the
United Nations, the World Trade Organization, the European Union
and other international organizations for ratification.
</P>
<P>
Poverty in diamond-producing countries in Africa must also be
addressed urgently, Hamutenya said.
</P>
<P>
"We are tired of Africa just being the source of rough
diamonds, "he said, calling for more cutting and polishing plants
to be established in the continent.
</P>
<P>
Although African countries mine the bulk of the world's rough
diamonds, most of the profit from the gems is made in European and
Asian cutting and trading centers, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
