<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Conservatives Raise Election Heat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Britain's main opposition
Conservative Party Tuesday increased the pace of preparations for
the next election with the publication of a draft manifesto.
</P>
<P>
The document, named "Believing in Britain," has been heralded
by Tory leader William Hague as containing the "key elements of a
bold program for the next Conservative government."
</P>
<P>
The program is -- for the first time -- to be voted on by the
whole membership of the Tory party before its October annual party
conference.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair is expected to call an early
general election next year, though he does not have to call one
until May 2002.
</P>
<P>
Launching "Believing in Britain," which brings together more
than 100 of the party's policies including a number of new ones,
Hague said he was determined to make Britain "the best place in
the world to do business and the best place in the world to live
and one of the most admired and influential countries in the world.
"
</P>
<P>
Defending his plans, Hague said millions of pounds could be
saved through cutting waste and driving up efficiency, and
reducing the size of Whitehall bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Europe, Hague committed the next Conservative
government to enshrining in law which powers the UK holds in
reserve against future encroachments by the European Commission or
the European courts.
</P>
<P>
He again underlined his party's determination to keep the pound
in the medium term, saying a Tory government would safeguard
sterling for at least the next parliament.
</P>
<P>
"Extraordinarily, the Conservatives will be the only major
party fighting the next election determined to stop the surrender
of our most precious right as a country -- the right to govern
ourselves," he said.
</P>
<P>
"By a combination of deliberate act and complacent failure to
act, within a decade, perhaps less, many of the things that make
our country a country, that make our nation a nation, that make
Britain 'Britain,' could have disappeared," he warned.
</P>
<P>
Turning to perhaps the most radical innovation of the document,
Hague detailed his party's plan to end state funding for
universities and instead to set them up with endowments.
</P>
<P>
He said that future auctions of assets like the recent third
generation of mobile phone licenses would be used to set up
endowment funds for universities, freeing them, he said, from
government control.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he repeated Tory plans to reduce the role of local
authorities in education and place more money directly in the
hands of individual schools.
</P>
<P>
Hague also said the document represented "a new Conservative
social agenda of devolving power to local people and local
institutions and local communities [which] shows that we have
listened and learnt, and that we trust the instincts of the
British people."
</P>
<P>
The manifesto also sets out plans to ensure Britain would
maintain its strong early position in the new information and
technology economy.
</P>
<P>
Believing in Britain promises that a future Tory government
would be "ruthless" about combating regulation
</P>
<P>
Hague also pledged to "reform the welfare state to strengthen
family life and personal responsibility" and promised new pension
arrangements for those young people who wanted them.
</P>
<P>
And on health, the Tory leader promised to take politicians out
of the day-to-day management of the National Health Service (NHS).
</P>
<P>
The intensification of campaigning by the Conservatives comes
as the Liberal Democrats prepare to release a similar mini-
manifesto Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
