<HEADLINE> Canadian Police Seize 156 Kilograms of Heroin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Canadian police have seized 156
kilograms of heroin for the past few days in the country's major
western city of Vancouver and eastern city of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
Of the 248 million Canadian dollars (about 168 million U.S.
dollars) worth of drug hauls, 99 kilograms were captured in
Vancouver Saturday and 57 kilograms in Toronto Thursday, the Royal
Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Police arrested a total of 11 suspects in the two separate drug
busts.
</P>
<P>
The heroin seizure was held as one of the largest in Canadian
history and a breakthrough leading to the drug Golden Triangle.
</P>
<P>
"The drug seizure is significant not only because of the
quantity of heroin seized, but because some of people arrested are
the alleged leaders of this major international smuggling
operation," said Vancouver RCMP Inspector Terry Town.
</P>
<P>
"There are only a few groups in the world that can orchestrate
this type of massive drug movement and we have obliterated this
one," the inspector added, declaring "the only enforcement step
higher would take us into the production fields of the Golden
Triangle."
</P>
<P>
Vancouver police said they had conducted a 20-month
investigation before making the drug bust. 
</P>
</TEXT>
