<HEADLINE> Worldwide Chip Sales Reach Record High in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide semiconductor
sales rose 50 percent to a record of 17.3 billion U.S. dollars in
July from a year ago, an American industry group reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chip sales were strong in all geographical regions due to
growth in demand for Internet infrastructure and wireless
communications, according to the Semiconductor Industry
Association (SIA). Sales in the Asia-Pacific region rose 57
percent. The European market was up 47 percent, while the U.S.,
Canada and Latin America rose a combined 46 percent. Japan sales
climbed 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
Intel and other chip makers have struggled this year to meet
demand for the chips that power everything from personal computers
to mobile phones, as consumers buy more devices to connect to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
In July 1999, worldwide chip sales reached 11.5 billion U.S.
dollars. The SIA predicts this year's sales will climb 31 percent
from last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
