<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Mixed With Blue Chips Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average gained a bit on surging financial service and retailer
stocks Tuesday, but the technology heavy Nasdaq composite index
fell sharply.
</P>
<P>
At the close of session, the Dow index rose 21.83 at 11,260.61
points, extending its gain of 23.68 last Friday. The market was
closed Monday for the labor Day Holiday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Nasdaq
composite fell 91.15 at 4,143.18 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index fell 13.69 at 1,507.08.
</P>
<P>
The Dow index moved higher amid continued merger speculation
after Credit Suisse First Boston said last week that it was
acquiring Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. J.P. Morgan, Citigroup and
American Express rose.
</P>
<P>
In the retailer sector, stocks of Home Depot and Wal-Mart
Stores surged, helping to drive the Dow higher.
</P>
<P>
But a selloff of Intel's stocks spread to the whole tech market,
dragging the Nasdaq index lower. Intel, the world's No. 1
semiconductor maker, headed lower after a Wall Street analyst
downgraded its rating for concerns with weakness in demand.
</P>
<P>
Computer maker stocks fell on the news. Dell and Gateway
dropped.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 1.38 at 676.20 and the Russell 2000 index
of smaller companies fell 2.89 at 539.02. But the American Stock
Exchange index rose 2.20 at 957.98.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a narrow margin, with
1,479 down, 1,435 up and 481 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 836.44 million shares from 766.47
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
