<HEADLINE> Security Council Extends U.N. Mission in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The council established the mission in October 1999 to
cooperate with the government of Sierra Leone and other parties to
implement the Lome Peace Agreement and to assist in the
implementation of the disarmament, demobilization and
reintegration plan.
</P>
<P>
The rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) reignited Sierra
Leone's nine-year civil war in May this year by seizing some 500 U.
N. peacekeepers which prompted the reassessment of the U.N.
mission.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan recommended last month that
the mission's mandate be extended for six months and its strength
increase to 20,500 from its current authorized ceiling of 13,000
to enhance its operational structure and overall effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
The current mandate of the mission expires on September 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
