<HEADLINE> Britain Sends Paratroopers to Senegal as S.Leone "Contingency" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Britain on Tuesday sent
paratroopers to West Africa as efforts continued to free six
British soldiers kidnapped by rebel groups in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
A British Defense Ministry spokesman said that 100
paratroopers were being sent to Dakar, Senegal, to position them
in the region should they be needed.
</P>
<P>
"It is a sensible contingency to keep our options open," a
Reuters report quoted the spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman denied that this military action was imminent
to free the hostages.
</P>
<P>
"Dialogue remains the most likely way that we are going to
resolve this situation, and military action is not imminent," he
said.
</P>
<P>
A rebel group in Sierra Leone, known as the West Side Boys,
seized 11 British soldiers as hostages late last month. But five
of the Britons were freed last week.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers were captured on a mission near Freetown, the
capital city of the Western African nation.
</P>
<P>
In the latest attempt to negotiate the freedom of the hostages,
Britain offered food and medicine to the West Side Boys' jungle
camp.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone, a former British colony, has been in military
chaos in recent years. Britain sent in 1,000 troops in May to help
the United Nations peacekeeping forces in Sierra Leone to maintain
peace. There are now nearly 400 British soldiers still in Sierra
Leone to help training a new Sierra Leone government army.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
