<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Announces Prescription Drug Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Republican presidential
candidate George W. Bush Tuesday unveiled a 158 billion dollar
plan to provide prescription drug benefit and to improve the
health care program for elderly Americans.
</P>
<P>
"We will honor our fathers and our mothers by providing quality
health insurance for every senior," Texas Governor Bush said in
his speech at a senior center in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
"For eight years the current administration has had this
opportunity and has squandered it," Bush added.
</P>
<P>
Under his plan, a total of 48 billion dollars will be provided
to states over four years to cover the full costs of a
prescription drug program for seniors with incomes below 11,300
dollars for individuals and 15,200 dollars for a couple.
</P>
<P>
His plan would also cover part of the costs of medicines for
individual seniors with incomes up to 14,600 dollars and couples
earning up to 19,700 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The plan would pay at least one-fourth of the cost of
prescription drug coverage, whether seniors choose the optional
new Medicare benefit Bush proposes or a private plan. The elderly
poor would get drug plans for free.
</P>
<P>
Bush's plan is expected to sharpen the debate over health care
between the Republican and Democratic parties.
</P>
<P>
Bush's Democratic rival Al Gore has proposed spending an
estimated 253 billion dollars over 10 years to add a prescription
drug benefit to Medicare, the federal program for elderly and
disabled Americans.
</P>
<P>
In response to Bush's plan, Vice President Gore said Bush's 158
million dollar package would not do enough for millions of middle-
class seniors.
</P>
<P>
"Nearly half of all of those who don't have coverage today
would not get coverage under the plan that he's announcing today,"
Gore said during a campaign stop in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
As Bush was promoting his prescription drug plan, the
Democratic National Committee Tuesday unveiled a new TV ad to run
this week in nine key states, criticizing Bush's health care
record. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
