<DOCNO> XIE20000905.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Rise in Worldwide Online Holiday Sales Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Explosive Internet access
growth will lead to an 85 percent increase in online holiday sales
worldwide this year, according to a report released Tuesday by a U.
S. market researcher.
</P>
<P>
Gartner Group predicted that worldwide online holiday sales
will reach 19.5 billion U.S. dollars from 10.5 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Canada will continue to account for more
than half of the sales this year with 10.7 billion dollars. Europe
will reach 5.4 billion dollars, while Asia-Pacific is projected to
gain 1.6 billion dollars. Sales in Japan are expected to rise more
than 180 percent to reach 1.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gartner noted strong demand for Western goods by the affluent
in Asia and support by governments, retail banks and card
companies.
</P>
<P>
Many consumers were making their first purchase over the
Internet during the holiday season last year. According to Gartner,
many Internet retailers were not prepared for the large number of
shoppers, so some Web sites had difficulties fulfilling orders in
time for the holidays. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
